'''Skyline''' is a [[light metro]] rapid transit system in the [[Honolulu County, Hawaii|City and County of Honolulu]] on the island of [[Oʻahu]], in the state of [[Hawaiʻi]]. Segment&nbsp;1 of the project, which lies entirely outside of the [[Urban Honolulu]] [[census-designated place]], opened on June&nbsp;30, 2023 linking [[East Kapolei, Hawaii|East Kapolei]] (on the [[ʻEwa]] Plain) and [[Aloha Stadium]] in [[Hālawa, Hawaii|Hālawa]]. Segment&nbsp;2, connecting to [[Pearl Harbor]], [[Daniel K. Inouye International Airport]] and [[Kahauiki station|Middle Street]], opened on October&nbsp;16, 2025. Segment&nbsp;3, continuing the line across Urban Honolulu to [[Downtown Honolulu|Downtown]], is due to open in 2031. The construction of Skyline constitutes the largest [[public works]] project in Hawaiʻi's history.

The {{Convert|18.9|mi|adj=on}}, automated fixed-guideway line was planned, designed, and constructed by the '''Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation''' ('''HART'''), a semi-autonomous government agency. Hitachi Rail, who also built the railcars used on the line, operates Skyline for the Honolulu Department of Transportation Services (which also manages the island's [[TheBus (Honolulu)|TheBus]] service). The almost entirely elevated line is the first large-scale, publicly run metro in the United States to feature [[platform screen doors]] and [[Automatic train operation|driverless trains]]. In {{American transit ridership|annualdate}}, the line had an annual ridership of {{American transit ridership|HI Honolulu HR annual}}, or about {{American transit ridership|HI Honolulu HR daily}} per day as of {{American transit ridership|dailydateasof}}.

==History==
Plans for a mass transit line to connect Honolulu's urban center with outlying areas began in the 1960s,<ref name="Blaisdell">{{Cite news |date=May 24, 1966 |title=Blaisdell hails Oahu mass transit project |pages=A12 |work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin}}</ref> but funding was not approved until 2005.<ref name="Reyes 2005">{{Cite news |last=Reyes |first=B.J. |date=August 11, 2005 |title=Council gives transit go-ahead 13 years after initial rejection |work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2005/08/11/news/story2.html |url-status=live |access-date=October 16, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100808202611/http://archives.starbulletin.com/2005/08/11/news/story2.html |archive-date=August 8, 2010}}</ref> Debate over the development of a rail system in Honolulu has been a major point of contention in local politics, especially leading into the 2008, [[2012 Honolulu mayoral election|2012]], and [[2016 Honolulu mayoral election|2016]] mayoral elections. Controversy over the rail line was the dominant issue for local politics in the late 2000s,<ref name="Carlson 2008">{{Cite news |last=Carlson |first=Ragnar |date=September 3, 2008 |title=Hail to the chief |work=Honolulu Weekly |url=http://honoluluweekly.com/cover/story-continued/2008/09/hail-to-the-chief/ |access-date=October 16, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928114114/http://honoluluweekly.com/cover/story-continued/2008/09/hail-to-the-chief/ |archive-date=September 28, 2011}}</ref> and culminated in a city charter amendment which left the final decision to a direct vote of the residents of Oʻahu.<ref name="Charter">{{Citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |title=Voters can derail $4B project |date=October 19, 2008 |url=http://www.starbulletin.com/news/hawaiinews/30935624.html |work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |access-date=March 8, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100601215930/http://www.starbulletin.com/news/hawaiinews/30935624.html |archive-date=June 1, 2010}}</ref> Construction of the rail line was approved by 53% of voters in November 2008,<ref name="53% S">{{Citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |title=Voters on route drive rail victory |date=November 10, 2008 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/content/20081110_Voters_on_route_drive_rail_victory |work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |access-date=July 7, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021164009/http://archives.starbulletin.com/content/20081110_Voters_on_route_drive_rail_victory |url-status=live |archive-date=October 21, 2012}}</ref> and ground broke on project construction on February 22, 2011.<ref name="Groundbreaking">{{Citation |last=Park |first=Gene |title=Rail ready to break ground |date=February 12, 2011 |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110212_rail_ready_to_break_ground.html |work=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |access-date=February 12, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924105920/http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110212_rail_ready_to_break_ground.html |url-status=live |archive-date=September 24, 2015}}</ref><ref name="Ground Broken">{{Citation |last=Park |first=Gene |title=It's a go! |date=February 23, 2011 |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110223_Its_a_go.html |work=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |volume=130 |issue=23 |page=A1 |access-date=February 23, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924105924/http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110223_Its_a_go.html |url-status=live |archive-date=September 24, 2015}}</ref>

===Previous projects===
For more than 50 years, some Honolulu politicians have attempted to construct a rail transit line. In 1966, then-mayor [[Neal S. Blaisdell]] suggested a rail line as a solution to alleviate traffic problems in Honolulu, stating, "Taken in the mass, the automobile is a noxious mechanism whose destiny in workaday urban use is to frustrate man and make dead certain that he approaches his daily occupation unhappy and inefficient."<ref name="Blaisdell" />

[[Frank Fasi]] was elected to office in 1968, and started planning studies for a rail project,<ref>{{Citation |title=Fasi To Start Rail Transit Study |date=February 16, 1969 |work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin & Advertiser |page=A1}} (Note: At this time, the ''Honolulu Star-Bulletin'' and ''Honolulu Advertiser'' published Sunday editions jointly under the name ''Honolulu Star-Bulletin & Advertiser''.)</ref> named Honolulu Area Rapid Transit (HART), in 1977.<ref>{{Citation |last=Tune |first=Jerry |title=A Transit Line with a HART |date=July 7, 1977 |work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |pages=A12}}</ref> After Fasi lost the 1980 reelection to [[Eileen Anderson]], President [[Ronald Reagan]] cut off funding for all upcoming mass transit projects, which led Anderson to cancel HART in 1981.<ref>{{Citation |last=Matsunaga |first=Mark |title=Reagan stops HART in its tracks |date=February 19, 1981 |work=Honolulu Advertiser |page=A1}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |last=Matsunaga |first=Mark |title=Mayor to abandon HART, beef up buses |date=May 5, 1981 |work=Honolulu Advertiser |pages=A1}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |last=Glauberman |first=Stu |title=Mayor Calls HART Study to Abrupt Halt |date=May 5, 1981 |work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |page=A1}}</ref> Fasi defeated Anderson in their 1984 rematch and restarted the HART project in 1986,<ref>{{Citation |last=Matsunaga |first=Mark |title=Transit system plan revived |date=August 14, 1986 |work=Honolulu Advertiser |page=A3}}</ref> but this second effort was stopped in a 1992 vote by the [[Honolulu City Council]] against the necessary tax increase.<ref name="Reyes 2005" /><ref>{{Citation |last=Mariani |first=Jeanne |title=Rail line dead – for now |date=September 23, 1992 |work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |page=A1}}</ref>

Fasi resigned in 1994 to run for governor, with [[Jeremy Harris (politician)|Jeremy Harris]] winning the [[By-election|special election]] to replace him. Harris unsuccessfully pursued a [[bus rapid transit]] project as an interim solution until he left office in 2004.<ref>{{Citation |last=Dicus |first=Howard |title=Harris: 'Honolulu must build fixed rail' |date=January 30, 2004 |url=http://pacific.bizjournals.com/pacific/stories/2004/01/26/daily64.html |work=Pacific Business News |access-date=October 16, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080706071818/http://pacific.bizjournals.com/pacific/stories/2004/01/26/daily64.html |url-status=live |archive-date=July 6, 2008}}</ref> His successor, [[Mufi Hannemann]], began the Honolulu High-Capacity Transit Corridor Project (HHCTCP), the island's fourth attempt to build a mass transit system operating in a dedicated right-of-way.

Hannemann thought it was "prudent to move quickly" to show the FTA that Honolulu was committed to the HHCTCP. An environmental impact study had not been completed at the time of signing the first construction contract with Kiewit. The FTA needed a complete environmental impact statement before moving Honolulu forward in the grant-awarding process. Hannemann's urge to move fast in the project ultimately allowed stakeholders to delay some important foundational work such as the environmental impact study.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Frosch |first1=Dan |last2=Overberg |first2=Paul |date=March 22, 2019 |title=How a Train Through Paradise Turned Into a $9 Billion Debacle |newspaper=Wall Street Journal |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-a-20-mile-train-line-swelled-into-a-9-billion-debacle-11553270393}}</ref>

===Studies===
[[File:City and County of Honolulu Honolulu High-Capacity Transit Corridor HCTC 63 Survey Marker Honolulu, Oahu, HI.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Honolulu High-Capacity Transit Corridor [[survey marker]] in the sidewalk at the corner of Kapʻiolani Boulevard and Keʻeaumoku Street in Honolulu.]]
The City and County of Honolulu Department of Transportation Services released the first formal study related to the HHCTCP on November 1, 2006, the ''Alternatives Analysis Report''. The report compared the cost and benefits of a "fixed guideway system", along with three alternatives. The first expanded the existing bus system to match [[population growth]]. A second option called for a further expansion to the bus system, with improvements to existing roads. The third alternative proposed a two-lane [[Overpass|flyover]] above the [[Interstate H-1|H-1 freeway]] between [[Pearl City, Hawaii|Pearl City]] and Honolulu International Airport, continuing over [[Hawaii Route 92|Nimitz Highway]], and into downtown Honolulu. The report recommended construction of the fixed guideway, and is considered the city's official justification for building a rail line.<ref name="AA Report Released">{{Citation |last=Kua |first=Crystal |title=Council panel backs rail as mass-transit solution |date=November 3, 2006 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2006/11/03/news/story07.html |work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |access-date=October 15, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081203174455/http://archives.starbulletin.com/2006/11/03/news/story07.html |url-status=live |archive-date=December 3, 2008}}</ref><ref>City and County of Honolulu Department of Transportation Services (November 1, 2006), ''Honolulu High-Capacity Transit Corridor Alternatives Analysis Report'' [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/Alterntives_Analysis_Toc_Chapter1.pdf Chapter 1]{{dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/Alterntives_Analysis_Chapter2.pdf Chapter 2]{{dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/Alterntives_Analysis_Chapter3_to_End.pdf Chapter 3 to 7]{{dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}, retrieved February 25, 2009</ref>

A second planning document, the ''Draft Environmental Impact Statement'' (DEIS), studied possible natural and social impacts of the construction and operation of the HHCTCP. The DEIS was completed and cleared for public release by the [[Federal Transit Administration]] (FTA) on October 29, 2008. After minor changes were made to comply with state law, the document was distributed via the city's official project website four days later. The DEIS indicated that impacts of the rail project would include land acquisition from private owners on the route, displacement of residents and businesses, aesthetic concerns related to the elevated guideway, and noise from passing trains.<ref>U.S. Department of Transportation Federal Transit Administration; City and County of Honolulu Department of Transportation Services, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/executive%20summary%20drafteis.pdf Draft Environmental Impact Statement Executive Summary]{{dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}} (PDF), retrieved February 25, 2009</ref>

The city was criticized for timing the release only two days before the 2008 general election. City Councilmember [[Ann Kobayashi]], running as a mayoral candidate against [[incumbent]] Hannemann, suggested that the city deliberately withheld key information to early voters who had already cast their ballots for the mayoral candidates, and a city charter amendment related to the project.<ref>{{Citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |title=City releases portion of rail report |date=October 31, 2008 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/content/20081031_City_releases_portion_of_rail_report |work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |access-date=July 7, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021164316/http://archives.starbulletin.com/content/20081031_City_releases_portion_of_rail_report |url-status=live |archive-date=October 21, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |last=Shikina |first=Robert |title=Kobayashi rails against city for timing of report |date=November 3, 2008 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/content/20081103_kobayashi_rails_against_city_for_timing_of_report |work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |access-date=November 6, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021172707/http://archives.starbulletin.com/content/20081103_kobayashi_rails_against_city_for_timing_of_report |url-status=live |archive-date=October 21, 2012}}</ref> The anti-rail advocacy group Stop Rail Now criticized the report for not further discussing bus rapid transit and toll lanes, options studied earlier by the city in its Alternatives Analysis.<ref>{{Citation |last1=Hao |first1=Sean |title=Hawaii rail transit cost now at least $4.34B |date=November 3, 2008 |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2008/Nov/03/ln/hawaii811030342.html |work=Honolulu Advertiser |access-date=March 5, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712220430/http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2008/Nov/03/ln/hawaii811030342.html |url-status=live |archive-date=July 12, 2011 |last2=Roig |first2=Suzanne}}</ref><ref>U.S. Department of Transportation Federal Transit Administration; City and County of Honolulu Department of Transportation Services (2008-11), ''Honolulu High-Capacity Transit Corridor Project Draft Environmental Impact Statement/Section 4(f) Evaluation'' [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/front.pdf Cover to Contents]{{dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/chapter%201.pdf Chapter 1] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110103143036/http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/chapter%201.pdf |date=January 3, 2011}}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/chapter%202.pdf Chapter 2] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110103144257/http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/chapter%202.pdf |date=January 3, 2011}}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/chapter%203.pdf Chapter 3]{{dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/chapter%204-front.pdf Chapter 4 (Part 1)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110103140420/http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/chapter%204-front.pdf |date=January 3, 2011}}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/chapter%204-end.pdf Chapter 4 (Part 2)]{{dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/chapter%205.pdf Chapter 5]{{dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/chapters%206%20to%208.pdf Chapters 6–8] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110103143502/http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/chapters%206%20to%208.pdf |date=January 3, 2011}}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/end.pdf References to Index] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100414182019/http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/end.pdf |date=April 14, 2010}}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/deis_appendix_a_1108.pdf Appendix A (Conceptual Alignment Plans and Profiles)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110103140528/http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/deis_appendix_a_1108.pdf |date=January 3, 2011}}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/deis_appendix_b_1108.pdf Appendix B (Conceptual Right-of-Way Plans)]{{dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/deis_appendix_c_1108.pdf Appendix C (Construction Approach)] {{Webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/5lwKtq3qH?url=http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/deis_appendix_c_1108.pdf |date=December 11, 2009}}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/deis_appendix_d_1108.pdf Appendix D (Record of Agency Correspondence and Coordination)]{{dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/deis_appendix_e_1108.pdf Appendix E (Record of Public and Stakeholder Correspondence and Coordination)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110103142549/http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/deis_appendix_e_1108.pdf |date=January 3, 2011}}, retrieved on January 5, 2009</ref>

The third and final official planning document, the Final Environmental Impact Statement (FEIS), was approved and cleared for public release by the FTA on June 14, 2010. The FEIS addresses and incorporates public comments received regarding the DEIS.<ref>{{Citation |last=Hao |first=Sean |title=Final study for rail line gets feds' OK |date=June 15, 2010 |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20100615_Final_study_for_rail_line_gets_feds_OK.html |work=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |access-date=February 1, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100620111508/http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20100615_Final_study_for_rail_line_gets_feds_OK.html |url-status=live |archive-date=June 20, 2010}}</ref> The FTA subsequently declared the environmental review process complete in a record of decision issued on January 18, 2011.<ref name="FTA RoD">{{Citation |last=Park |first=Gene |title=Rail gets OK to break ground |date=January 19, 2011 |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110119_Rail_gets_OK_to_break_ground.html |work=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |access-date=January 20, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110122081327/http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110119_Rail_gets_OK_to_break_ground.html |url-status=live |archive-date=January 22, 2011}}</ref>

===Native burials===
Like most major infrastructure work in Hawaiʻi, construction of the rail line was likely to uncover historic human remains, notably in its downtown Honolulu section. The Oʻahu Island Burial Council (part of the State Historic Preservation Division, within the State of Hawaiʻi Department of Land and Natural Resources) refused to sign a programmatic agreement on October 21, 2009, over concerns about likely burial sites located along the line's proposed route over Halekauwila Street in [[Kakaako|Kakaʻako]]. Three construction projects in the area since 2002 have each encountered unforeseen human remains that led to delays, and [[archaeologist]] Thomas Dye stated, "The council is absolutely right that you should expect to find burials on Halekauwila Street".<ref name="2009-10 Burials">{{Citation |last=Hao |first=Sean |title=Burial council won't sign rail pact |date=October 20, 2009 |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2009/Oct/20/ln/hawaii910200360.html |work=Honolulu Advertiser |access-date=July 7, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610040614/http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2009/Oct/20/ln/hawaii910200360.html |url-status=live |archive-date=June 10, 2011}}</ref>

The Burial Council's core contention was the city's decision to conduct an archaeological survey of the rail line's route in phases, meaning construction on a majority of the line will be complete by the time the survey in the Kakaʻako area is performed, which in turn would increase the likelihood that any remains discovered would be moved instead of being allowed to remain ''in situ''.<ref>{{Citation |last=Conrow |first=Joan |title=grave matters |date=May 26, 2010 |url=http://honoluluweekly.com/cover/2010/05/grave-matters/ |work=Honolulu Weekly |access-date=January 30, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111119140503/http://honoluluweekly.com/cover/2010/05/grave-matters/ |archive-date=November 19, 2011}}</ref> In response to the Burial Council's concerns, the city agreed to begin conducting an archaeological survey of the area in 2010, two years earlier than originally planned.<ref name="2009-10 Burials" /> The state Department of Land and Natural Resources later signed the city's programmatic agreement on January 15, 2011, over the continuing concerns of the Burial Council.<ref>{{Citation |last=Park |first=Gene |title=City plan accounts for problematic burial sites |date=January 16, 2011 |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110116_City_plan_accounts_for_problematic_burial_sites.html |work=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |access-date=January 30, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110119144127/http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110116_City_plan_accounts_for_problematic_burial_sites.html |url-status=live |archive-date=January 19, 2011}}</ref>

The city's decision to conduct the archaeological survey in phases subsequently led to a lawsuit filed on February 1, 2011, by the [[Native Hawaiian Legal Corporation]] on behalf of cultural practitioner Paulette Kaleikini. The suit, which named both the city and the State of Hawaiʻi as defendants, contended that state law required the full length of the rail line to have an archaeological survey conducted before any construction took place, and sought to void the environmental impact statement and all construction permits issued for the project.<ref>{{Citation |last=Daranciang |first=Nelson |title=Lawsuit claims rail endangers burial sites |date=February 1, 2011 |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110202_Lawsuit_claims_rail_endangers_burial_sites.html |work=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |volume=129 |issue=364 |page=B1 |access-date=February 1, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110213094548/http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110202_Lawsuit_claims_rail_endangers_burial_sites.html |url-status=live |archive-date=February 13, 2011}}</ref> Kaleikini's lawyers filed on February 18 a request for an injunction to stop work on the project until the case was resolved.<ref name="Ground Broken" /> The suit was initially dismissed in March 2011 by Circuit Court Judge Gary Chang.<ref>{{Citation |last=Daranciang |first=Nelson |title=Judge Rejects Suit Challenging Rail Survey |date=March 24, 2011 |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110324__Judge_rejects_suit_challenging_rail_survey.html |work=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |access-date=March 24, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120918115125/http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110324__Judge_rejects_suit_challenging_rail_survey.html |url-status=live |archive-date=September 18, 2012}}</ref> However, after Kaleikini's lawyers appealed,<ref>{{Citation |last=Hervey |first=Tiffany |title=Buried Truth |date=June 27, 2012 |url=http://honoluluweekly.com/feature/2012/06/buried-truth/ |work=Honolulu Weekly |access-date=July 19, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025223421/http://honoluluweekly.com/feature/2012/06/buried-truth/ |archive-date=October 25, 2012}}</ref> the Hawaiʻi Supreme Court ruled in August 2012 in the plaintiff's favor, finding that the State Historic Preservation Division did not comply with state law when it approved the project. The case was then [[Remand (court procedure)|remanded]] to Circuit Court.<ref>{{Citation |last=Grube |first=Nick |title=Rail Derailed? Hawaii Supreme Court Rules Against Honolulu |date=August 24, 2012 |url=http://www.civilbeat.com/articles/2012/08/24/16937-rail-derailed-hawaii-supreme-court-rules-against-honolulu/ |work=[[Honolulu Civil Beat]] |access-date=August 24, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105034104/http://www.civilbeat.com/articles/2012/08/24/16937-rail-derailed-hawaii-supreme-court-rules-against-honolulu/ |url-status=live |publisher=Peer News LLC |archive-date=November 5, 2013}}</ref> In December 2012, the [[United States District Court for the District of Hawaii]] granted the plaintiffs' injunction, and ordered that all construction-related activities be halted until compliance with the Hawaiʻi Supreme Court decision was met. Judge Tashima, the sitting judge on the case, ruled that the city is required to file periodic status updates on their compliance with the judgment. The injunction would then terminate 30 days after defendants filed a notice of final compliance.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Schwind |first=Paul |date=January 3, 2013 |title=Honolulu Rail Remedy – Phasers On Minimal |url=http://www.hawaiireporter.com/honolulu-rail-remedy-phasers-on-minimal/123 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105032128/http://www.hawaiireporter.com/honolulu-rail-remedy-phasers-on-minimal/123 |archive-date=November 5, 2013 |access-date=January 17, 2013 |website=Web |publisher=Hawaii Reporter}}</ref>

In February 2013, the rail authority said that they had completed the required archaeological surveys and that construction would resume later that year. The agency reported that remains were discovered at seven sites in the downtown area, and that if it was decided to leave them in place, then they "would be able to adjust the final design to accommodate that request".<ref>{{Cite web |last=<!--not stated--> |date=2013-02-05 |title=Honolulu Rail Authority: Archeological Survey Mandated by Court is Done Ahead of Schedule |url=https://www.hawaiireporter.com/honolulu-rail-authority-archeological-survey-mandated-by-the-supreme-court-is-done-ahead-of-schedule/ |access-date=2026-01-01 |website=Hawaii Reporter |language=en-US}}</ref>

===Impact on Honolulu mayoral elections===
The importance of the Honolulu High-Capacity Transit Corridor Project in the 2008 mayoral election led one observer to describe the vote as a "referendum on rail transit".<ref name="Carlson 2008" /> Two challengers emerged as rivals to incumbent [[Mufi Hannemann]]: City Councilmember [[Ann Kobayashi]] and [[University of Hawaiʻi]] professor [[Panos Prevedouros]]. Kobayashi supported a [[Rubber-tyred metro|rubber-tired]] mass transit system as opposed to the conventional system chosen by the Hannemann administration. Prevedouros, on the other hand, as a noted highway advocate, opposed any type of mass transit project and instead favored construction of a reversible tollway over the [[Interstate H-1|H-1 freeway]] (similar to the Managed Lane option, which the Alternatives Analysis studied and rejected as unworkable, instead reworking existing road systems to ease congestion).<ref>{{Citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |title=Mayoral debate turns raucous |date=September 10, 2008 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/09/10/news/story01.html |work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |access-date=October 16, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090124174059/http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/09/10/news/story01.html |url-status=live |archive-date=January 24, 2009}}</ref> No candidate won a majority of votes in the September 20 primary, forcing a runoff between Hannemann and Kobayashi;<ref>{{Citation |last1=Borreca |first1=Richard |title=Hannemann and Kobayashi reset sights for Nov. 4 |date=September 21, 2008 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/09/21/news/story01.html |work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |access-date=October 20, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080925001828/http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/09/21/news/story01.html |url-status=live |archive-date=September 25, 2008 |last2=Au |first2=Laurie}}</ref> Hannemann successfully retained his post with 58% of the vote in the November 4 general election.<ref>{{Citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |title=Hannemann win re-election with 58% |date=November 5, 2008 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/content/20081105_Hannemann_wins_re-election_with_58 |work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |access-date=November 5, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021172726/http://archives.starbulletin.com/content/20081105_Hannemann_wins_re-election_with_58 |url-status=live |archive-date=October 21, 2012}}</ref>

On April 22, 2008, the Stop Rail Now advocacy group announced their intent to file a petition with the city to place a question on the 2008 [[ballot]] to create an ordinance that read: "Honolulu mass transit shall not include trains or rail".<ref>{{Citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |title=Rail critics utilize power of pen |date=April 22, 2008 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/04/22/news/story01.html |work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |access-date=October 20, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100807164627/http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/04/22/news/story01.html |url-status=live |archive-date=August 7, 2010}}</ref> Stop Rail Now attempted to submit the petition with 49,041 signatures on August 5, but was initially denied after the city clerk claimed the city charter did not allow the petition to be submitted less than 180 days before a general election, as the wording of the petition called for a special election.<ref>{{Citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |title=Lawsuit looms over validity of anti-rail petition |date=August 5, 2008 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/08/05/news/story03.html |work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |access-date=November 6, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221005855/http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/08/05/news/story03.html |url-status=live |archive-date=February 21, 2009}}</ref><ref>[http://www.honolulu.gov/refs/rch/rc030404.pdf Section 3-404] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080918152900/http://www.honolulu.gov/refs/rch/rc030404.pdf |date=September 18, 2008}} (PDF), [http://www.honolulu.gov/refs/rch/ Revised Charter of Honolulu] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080907150738/http://www.honolulu.gov/refs/rch/ |date=September 7, 2008}}, retrieved on February 25, 2009</ref> The group filed a lawsuit to force the city to accept the petition, and the courts ruled in Stop Rail Now's favor on August 14.<ref>{{Citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |title=City clerk rushing to certify anti-rail effort |date=August 20, 2008 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/08/20/news/story07.html |work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |access-date=November 6, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091209061744/http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/08/20/news/story07.html |url-status=live |archive-date=December 9, 2009}}</ref> Stop Rail Now's effort ultimately failed on September 4 when the city clerk deemed only 35,056 of the signatures valid, well short of the 44,525 required.<ref>{{Citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |title=Anti-rail group's effort denied by courts, clerk |date=September 4, 2008 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/09/04/news/story03.html |work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |access-date=November 6, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080927074754/http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/09/04/news/story03.html |url-status=live |archive-date=September 27, 2008}}</ref>

In response to the possibility that Stop Rail Now's petition would fail, the City Council had however voted on August 21 to place a proposed amendment to the city charter on the ballot, asking voters to decide the fate of the project.<ref>{{Citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |title=Council OKs ballot question on transit |date=August 21, 2008 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/08/21/news/story02.html |work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |access-date=November 12, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090924041556/http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/08/21/news/story02.html |url-status=live |archive-date=September 24, 2009}}</ref> Mayor Hannemann signed the proposal the following day.<ref>{{Citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |title=Mayor vows to put transit on ballot |date=August 22, 2008 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/08/22/news/story04.html |work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |access-date=November 12, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090904052558/http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/08/22/news/story04.html |url-status=live |archive-date=September 4, 2009}}</ref> The City Council's proposed amendment was not intended to have a direct legal effect on the city's ability to continue the project, but was meant as a means for Oahu residents to express their opinions on its construction.<ref name="Charter" /> The charter amendment was approved with 53% of votes cast in favor of rail and 47% against. Majorities of voters in Leeward and Central Oahu, the areas that will be served by the project, voted in favor of the amendment, while the majority of those living outside the project's scope in Windward Oahu and [[East Honolulu, Hawaii|East Honolulu]] voted against it.<ref name="53% S" /> In mid-2010, Hannemann resigned as mayor to run for governor and Kirk Caldwell assumed the position of interim mayor.<ref name="Dayton2019-01-11">{{Cite news |last=Dayton |first=Kevin |date=January 11, 2019 |title=Premature contracts increased rail cost by $354M |work=[[Star-Advertiser]] |location=[[Honolulu]] |url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2019/01/11/hawaii-news/premature-contracts-increased-rail-cost-by-354m/?HSA=eb247f207a1158b53d1b48d5858ca2997cc4061a |url-status=live |access-date=January 11, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317230702/https://www.staradvertiser.com/2019/01/11/hawaii-news/premature-contracts-increased-rail-cost-by-354m/?HSA=eb247f207a1158b53d1b48d5858ca2997cc4061a |archive-date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>

In the [[2016 Honolulu mayoral election]], the main three candidates again took opposing views on rail. Honolulu City Council Member [[Charles Djou]], former mayor [[Peter Carlisle]], and incumbent [[Kirk Caldwell]] all ran with the stated goal of finishing the project. However, Republican candidate Djou ran on a platform of drastically cutting spending on rail by cutting funding on buying cars on the rail before its completion and hiring mainland consultants.<ref>Charles Djou, "Rail" (http://djou.com/issues/rail/ {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161030235612/http://djou.com/issues/rail/ |date=October 30, 2016}})</ref>{{Clarify|date=October 2025}} Caldwell also stated that spending on rail should be cut, but instead believed that the line should be shortened to end at Middle Street.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Mendoza |first1=Jim |last2=Lincoln |first2=Mileka |last3=Davis |first3=Chelsea |date=June 16, 2016 |title=Mayor wants to shorten rail route, ending at Middle Street |language=en |work=Hawaii News Now |url=http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/32242522/caldwell-wants-to-shorten-rail-to-15-miles-ending-route-at-middle-street |url-status=live |access-date=March 11, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170403015224/http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/32242522/caldwell-wants-to-shorten-rail-to-15-miles-ending-route-at-middle-street |archive-date=April 3, 2017}}</ref> Carlisle was the only candidate in support of funding the full rail system, staying that rail has progressed too far to be stopped midway.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Lee |first=Grace |date=May 18, 2016 |title=Mayoral candidate Peter Carlisle says rail project cannot be stopped |url=https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/31997123/mayoral-candidate-peter-carl-isle-says-rail-project-cannot-be-stopped |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230709194915/https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/31997123/mayoral-candidate-peter-carl-isle-says-rail-project-cannot-be-stopped/ |archive-date=July 9, 2023 |access-date=June 15, 2024 |website=[[Hawaii News Now]]}}</ref> While Caldwell won the election, he quickly adopted Carlisle's position that the project should be seen through to completion.

===Delays and cost overruns===
[[File:Hart-wordmark.svg|thumb|Logo of the Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation (HART), the semi-autonomous government agency which built the line.]]

Construction on the rail line was originally scheduled to begin in December 2009 but did not occur due to delays in the project review process and in obtaining federal approval of the environmental impact statement.<ref>{{Citation |last=Hao |first=Sean |title=Honolulu rail behind schedule, with construction start unclear |date=January 3, 2010 |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2010/Jan/03/ln/hawaii1030376.html |work=Honolulu Advertiser |access-date=February 1, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101214161817/http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2010/Jan/03/ln/hawaii1030376.html |url-status=live |archive-date=December 14, 2010}}</ref>

[[File:Honolulu Mayor Peter Carlisle at Rail Groundbreaking 2011-02-22.jpg|thumb|Former Honolulu mayor [[Peter Carlisle]] speaking at the project's groundbreaking ceremony.]]

In January 2010, Republican Governor [[Linda Lingle]] publicly recommended that the city alter plans for the rail line after news reports on FTA documents revealed that the agency raised issues over declining tax revenues in connection with a [[Late-2000s recession|global economic recession]],<ref>{{Citation |last1=Hao |first1=Sean |title=Honolulu's rail costs put state at financial risk, governor says |date=January 9, 2010 |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2010/Jan/09/ln/hawaii1090342.html |work=Honolulu Advertiser |access-date=February 1, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101214171704/http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2010/Jan/09/ln/hawaii1090342.html |url-status=live |archive-date=December 14, 2010 |last2=Pang |first2=Gordon Y.K.}}</ref> and commissioned a study by the state to review the project's finances in March.<ref>{{Citation |last=Hao |first=Sean |title=Time short for Lingle's call on rail |date=August 26, 2010 |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20100826_Time_short_for_Lingles_call_on_rail.html |work=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |access-date=February 1, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100829052439/http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20100826_Time_short_for_Lingles_call_on_rail.html |url-status=live |archive-date=August 29, 2010}}</ref> The state financial study, publicly released on December 2, 2010, indicated that the project would likely experience a $1.7 billion overrun above the $5.3 billion projected cost, and that collections from the state's [[Excise tax in the United States|General Excise Tax]] would be 30% below forecasts. The study was dismissed as "damaged goods" and "a pre-determined anti-rail rant" by Democratic mayor Peter Carlisle. He also pointed out that several conclusions were "erroneous" and "inaccurate", before concluding that "spending a third of a million dollars for this shoddy, biased analysis is an appalling waste of our tax dollars."<ref name="LingleReport2010">{{Cite web |date=December 3, 2010 |title=Carlisle dismisses Lingle's rail report |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/blog/2010/12/carlisle-honolulus-rail-project.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170806141408/https://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/blog/2010/12/carlisle-honolulus-rail-project.html |archive-date=August 6, 2017 |access-date=September 1, 2017 |website=Pacific Business News}}</ref> Lingle's Democratic successor, [[Neil Abercrombie]], publicly stated that the financial analysis would not affect his decision to approve or disapprove of the project, saying that the state's responsibility is limited to the environmental review process, and that decisions regarding the project's finances belong to the city and the FTA.<ref>{{Citation |last=DePledge |first=Derrick |title=Abercrombie to weigh rail EIS |date=November 5, 2010 |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/hawaiinews/20101105_Abercrombie_to_weigh_rail_EIS.html |work=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |access-date=February 1, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120913053156/http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/hawaiinews/20101105_Abercrombie_to_weigh_rail_EIS.html |url-status=live |archive-date=September 13, 2012}}</ref> Governor Abercrombie subsequently approved the project's final environmental impact statement on December 16, 2010.<ref>{{Citation |last=Park |first=Gene |title=Governor signs off on review of rail |date=December 17, 2010 |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20101217_Governor_signs_off_on_review_of_rail.html |work=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |access-date=February 1, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110120144013/http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20101217_Governor_signs_off_on_review_of_rail.html |url-status=live |archive-date=January 20, 2011}}</ref> The Honolulu City Council held a hearing on January 12, 2011 about the state's financial review, but the hearing was not attended by any state officials, who had been invited to testify.<ref>{{Citation |last=Park |first=Gene |title=State skips hearing on rail finance studies |date=January 13, 2011 |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/hawaiinews/20110113_State_skips_hearing_on_rail_finance_studies.html |work=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |access-date=February 1, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120913053302/http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/hawaiinews/20110113_State_skips_hearing_on_rail_finance_studies.html |url-status=live |archive-date=September 13, 2012}}</ref>

On January 18, 2011, the FTA issued a "record of decision", indicating that the project had met the requirements of its environmental review and that the city was allowed to begin construction work on the project.<ref name="FTA RoD" /> The record of decision allowed the city to begin negotiating with owners of land that will be purchased for the project, to begin relocating utility lines to make way for construction of the line and stations, and to purchase [[rolling stock]] for the rail line.<ref>{{Citation |last=Park |first=Gene |title=If they build it, will developers come? |date=February 20, 2011 |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110220_If_they_build_it_will_developers_come.html |work=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |access-date=February 20, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110222223636/http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110220_If_they_build_it_will_developers_come.html |url-status=live |archive-date=February 22, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |last=LaFrance |first=Adrienne |title=Rail Groundbreaking: Phony or For Real? |date=February 21, 2011 |url=http://www.civilbeat.com/articles/2011/02/21/9126-rail-groundbreaking-phony-or-for-real/ |work=Honolulu Civil Beat |access-date=February 22, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110301080421/http://www.civilbeat.com/articles/2011/02/21/9126-rail-groundbreaking-phony-or-for-real/ |url-status=live |publisher=Peer News LLC |archive-date=March 1, 2011}}</ref> A ground-breaking ceremony was held on February 22, 2011, in Kapolei, at the site of the future East Kapolei station along Kualakai Parkway.<ref name="Groundbreaking" /><ref name="Ground Broken" />

The City and County of Honolulu established the Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation (HART) on July 1, 2011. HART is a semi-autonomous government agency authorized to develop, operate, maintain, and expand the rail system. HART is led by its own Board of Directors, which appoints an Executive Director/CEO to provide leadership, direction and supervision of the day-to-day business activities of the agency.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2013 |title=Chapter 22 Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |url=https://www.honolulu.gov/rep/site/oca/sea_chapters_fy2010/Chapter_22_HART.pdf |website=City and County of Honolulu |access-date=June 21, 2024 |archive-date=June 21, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240621234840/https://www.honolulu.gov/rep/site/oca/sea_chapters_fy2010/Chapter_22_HART.pdf |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=About |url=https://honolulutransit.org/about/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230601122709/https://honolulutransit.org/about/ |archive-date=June 1, 2023 |access-date=June 19, 2023 |website=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation}}</ref>

In March 2012, [[Daniel Grabauskas|Dan Grabauskas]] was hired on a three-year contract as the first Executive Director/CEO of HART.<ref name="HonoluluGov2012-03-01">{{Cite news |date=March 1, 2012 |title=Danial Grabauskas Named HART Executive Director |work=City and County of Honolulu: Department of Customer Services |url=https://www.honolulu.gov/csd-news-2012/5840-03-01-12-daniel-grabauskas-named-hart-executive-director.html |url-status=live |access-date=January 11, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180511124553/https://www.honolulu.gov/csd-news-2012/5840-03-01-12-daniel-grabauskas-named-hart-executive-director.html |archive-date=May 11, 2018}}</ref> In 2014 HART CEO Dan Grabauskas blamed lawsuits, launched in 2011, for some of the cost overruns after bids to construct the first nine stations exceeded the budget by $100 million. His claims were disputed by the plaintiffs in one of the cases, who said HART could have put the stations out to tender and that HART had deliberately delayed the legal proceedings so a judgment would only be delivered after a significant proportion of the line had been completed.<ref>{{Cite web |date=August 15, 2014 |title=Honolulu rail CEO blames cost overruns on legal challenges, but critics say it is incompetence |url=http://www.hawaiireporter.com/honolulu-rail-ceo-blames-cost-overruns-on-legal-challenges-but-critics-say-it-is-incompetence |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170906134610/http://www.hawaiireporter.com/honolulu-rail-ceo-blames-cost-overruns-on-legal-challenges-but-critics-say-it-is-incompetence |archive-date=September 6, 2017 |access-date=September 6, 2017}}</ref>

In August 2016, Grabauskas resigned as HART director amid criticism of his leadership by the HART board. Michael Formby was appointed interim director.<ref name="StarAdvertiser2016-08-16" />

===Testing and more delays===
Interim service over the first ten miles of the line, between East Kapolei and Aloha Stadium, was scheduled to commence in October 2020. However, complications due to the [[COVID-19 pandemic]] pushed the start date back by three months.<ref>{{Cite news |date=May 16, 2020 |title=Editorial: COVID-19 brings more delays and money problems for Honolulu's rail |agency=Honolulu Star Advertiser |url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2020/05/16/editorial/our-view/editorial-covid-19-brings-more-delays-and-money-problems-for-honolulus-rail/ |url-status=live |access-date=May 25, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200523115324/https://www.staradvertiser.com/2020/05/16/editorial/our-view/editorial-covid-19-brings-more-delays-and-money-problems-for-honolulus-rail/ |archive-date=May 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Honore |first=Marcel |date=May 12, 2020 |title=City Council Grows Anxious As Rail's COVID-19 Problems Deepen |agency=Honolulu Civil Beat |url=https://www.civilbeat.org/2020/05/city-council-grows-anxious-as-rails-covid-19-problems-deepen/ |url-status=live |access-date=May 25, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200523155955/https://www.civilbeat.org/2020/05/city-council-grows-anxious-as-rails-covid-19-problems-deepen/ |archive-date=May 23, 2020}}</ref> By November 2020, the opening had again slipped to late 2021 due to delays in testing equipment.<ref name="Honore2020">{{Cite news |last=Honore |first=Marcel |date=November 24, 2020 |title=Rail's Interim Service Could Be Pushed Back A Year Amid COVID-19, Testing Woes |agency=Honolulu Civil Beat |url=https://www.civilbeat.org/2020/11/rails-interim-service-could-be-pushed-back-a-year-amid-covid-testing-woes/ |url-status=live |access-date=January 2, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210105133605/https://www.civilbeat.org/2020/11/rails-interim-service-could-be-pushed-back-a-year-amid-covid-testing-woes/ |archive-date=January 5, 2021}}</ref>

In December 2020, HART discovered early wear on the track crossings, or "frogs". It was later determined that the trains' wheel flanges were approximately {{convert|1/2|in|spell=in}} narrower at the frogs, thus affecting the driverless trains' ability to safely navigate certain track crossings at the speeds needed to operate on schedule. During investigation, subpar welding and sandblasting-induced cracks were also discovered.<ref>{{Cite web |date=March 19, 2021 |title=HART, Hitachi At Odds Over Wheel Defect As Rail Costs Soar |url=https://www.civilbeat.org/2021/03/hart-hitachi-at-odds-over-wheel-defect-as-rail-costs-soar/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210514085429/https://www.civilbeat.org/2021/03/hart-hitachi-at-odds-over-wheel-defect-as-rail-costs-soar/ |archive-date=May 14, 2021 |access-date=May 14, 2021 |website=Honolulu Civil Beat |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=May 7, 2021 |title=Wheels don't fit tracks on Honolulu's beleaguered rail line |url=https://apnews.com/article/honolulu-8a0bd1342d1e0fd9cb33cf88f2820840 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210514085428/https://apnews.com/article/honolulu-8a0bd1342d1e0fd9cb33cf88f2820840 |archive-date=May 14, 2021 |access-date=May 14, 2021 |website=AP NEWS}}</ref> In November 2021, Roger Morton, director of Honolulu's Department of Transportation Services, stated that a required three months of field testing and certification (to be carried out by Hitachi) was scheduled to begin in January 2022.<ref name="HB-2021">{{Cite news |last=Fuji-Oride |first=Noelle |date=November 9, 2021 |title=How Rail Got to $12.45 Billion and 11 Years Late |work=[[Hawaii Business]] |url=https://www.hawaiibusiness.com/hart-history-hawaii-rail-project-when-finished-budget/ |url-status=live |access-date=November 18, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220127005320/https://www.hawaiibusiness.com/hart-history-hawaii-rail-project-when-finished-budget/ |archive-date=January 27, 2022}}</ref>

In December 2021, it was decided that temporary welding fixes would be made to allow the trains to run at operational speeds despite the narrower wheels, with plans to swap out wheels with wider ones during future maintenance work. An initial call searching for contractors to perform the manganese welding work failed to return any bids.<ref>{{Cite news |date=December 8, 2021 |title=Honolulu rail CEO offers new hope to repair gap between rail wheels and track |agency=Honolulu Star Advertiser |url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2021/12/08/breaking-news/honolulu-rail-ceo-offers-new-hope-to-repair-gap-between-rail-wheels-and-track/ |url-status=live |access-date=January 28, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220128142300/https://www.staradvertiser.com/2021/12/08/breaking-news/honolulu-rail-ceo-offers-new-hope-to-repair-gap-between-rail-wheels-and-track/ |archive-date=January 28, 2022}}</ref> Due to the lack of local companies able to complete the work, the state's Department of Commerce and Consumer Affairs granted HART an exemption allowing mainland contractors to be hired.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Honore |first=Marcel |date=November 9, 2021 |title=HART Has A Plan To Fix Rail Tracks But Lacks Welders To Do The Work |agency=Honolulu Civil Beat |url=https://www.civilbeat.org/2021/11/hart-has-a-plan-to-fix-the-rail-tracks-but-lacks-welders-to-do-the-work/ |url-status=live |access-date=January 28, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220128142300/https://www.civilbeat.org/2021/11/hart-has-a-plan-to-fix-the-rail-tracks-but-lacks-welders-to-do-the-work/ |archive-date=January 28, 2022}}</ref>

===Social impact===
Proponents of the system say it will alleviate worsening [[traffic congestion]], already among the worst in the United States.<ref name="worsttraffic">{{Cite web |date=May 23, 2012 |title=Honolulu ranked worst in country for traffic |url=http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/18599683/honolulu-ranked-worst-in-country-for-traffic |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914100417/http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/18599683/honolulu-ranked-worst-in-country-for-traffic |archive-date=September 14, 2017 |access-date=August 31, 2017 |website=Hawaii News Now}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Honolulu Rail Final EIS, Table 3-12 |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-16806/20110701-final-eis-chapter-03.pdf |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220126212044/http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-16806/20110701-final-eis-chapter-03.pdf |archive-date=January 26, 2022 |access-date=November 4, 2020 |website=hartdocs.honolulu.gov}}</ref> They assert that the long and narrow urban agglomeration in south Oʻahu is ideally suited to rail, and that highway expansion will only lead to [[induced demand]]. In opposition, freeway advocate [[Panos Prevedouros]] has questioned its cost-effectiveness compared to "road widening or lane addition", and speculated in 2015 that it "will never provide any congestion relief for the traveling public".<ref name="worsttraffic" /><ref>{{Cite web |date=January 29, 2015 |title=What Can We Do About the Rail? Nothing. Tackle Traffic Congestion! |url=http://www.civilbeat.org/2015/01/what-can-we-do-about-the-rail-nothing-tackle-traffic-congestion/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831173354/http://www.civilbeat.org/2015/01/what-can-we-do-about-the-rail-nothing-tackle-traffic-congestion/ |archive-date=August 31, 2017 |access-date=August 31, 2017 |publisher=[[Honolulu Civil Beat]]}}</ref>

==Financing==
Construction of Skyline is financed by a surcharge on local taxes as well as a $1.55&nbsp;billion grant from the [[Federal Transit Administration]] (FTA). After major cost overruns, the tax surcharges were extended in 2016 by five years to raise another $1.2&nbsp;billion; however that additional funding was only sufficient for construction out to Middle Street in [[Kalihi]]. The FTA stated that its contribution is contingent to completion of the line all the way to Ala Moana Center, and will not be increased.<ref name="CRAIGT.KOJIMA">{{Cite news |last=Kojima |first=Craig T. |date=2016 |title=Feds to city: No more money for rail, no stopping at Middle Street |work=Honolulu Star Advertiser |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/breaking-news/fta-says-no-to-stopping-rail-at-middle-street-additional-funding/ |url-status=live |access-date=August 31, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160901152636/http://www.staradvertiser.com/breaking-news/fta-says-no-to-stopping-rail-at-middle-street-additional-funding/ |archive-date=September 1, 2016}}</ref> After much wrangling, the state legislature in 2017 approved $2.4&nbsp;billion in additional taxes to allow the city to complete the project according to the original plan.<ref name="Nanea.Kalani">{{Cite news |last=Nanea Kalani |date=September 1, 2017 |title=Rail bail-out bill goes to Ige after House approves |work=Honolulu Star Advertiser |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2017/09/01/breaking-news/rail-bail-out-bill-goes-to-ige-after-house-approves/ |url-status=live |access-date=September 2, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170902024506/http://www.staradvertiser.com/2017/09/01/breaking-news/rail-bail-out-bill-goes-to-ige-after-house-approves/ |archive-date=September 2, 2017}}</ref>

The process to award the contract for building the final {{convert|4.3|mi|km|adj=on}} section through downtown Honolulu was suspended in 2015. The process was restarted in September 2017,<ref>{{Cite news |date=September 8, 2017 |title=Rail officials start over on selecting builder for last stretch |work=Honolulu Star Advertiser |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2017/09/07/hawaii-news/rail-officials-start-over-on-selecting-builder-for-last-stretch/?HSA=af10a21d7a7762a176d7320f3ad163e48af2b7c4 |url-status=live |access-date=September 25, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201125024126/https://www.staradvertiser.com/2017/09/07/hawaii-news/rail-officials-start-over-on-selecting-builder-for-last-stretch/?HSA=af10a21d7a7762a176d7320f3ad163e48af2b7c4 |archive-date=November 25, 2020}}</ref> and the first major contract for that section, estimated at $400 million, was awarded in May 2018.<ref name="HSA-180507" />

The final cost has grown from preliminary projections of $4&nbsp;billion in 2006<ref name="2006cost3billion" /> to as much as $12.4&nbsp;billion by 2021.<ref>{{Cite news |date=August 9, 2021 |title=For Cost Overruns, Honolulu Rail Is In A League Of Its Own, New Data Shows |work=Honolulu Civil Beat |url=https://www.civilbeat.org/2021/08/for-cost-overruns-honolulu-rail-is-in-a-league-of-its-own-new-data-shows/ |url-status=live |access-date=September 11, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210911154426/https://www.civilbeat.org/2021/08/for-cost-overruns-honolulu-rail-is-in-a-league-of-its-own-new-data-shows/ |archive-date=September 11, 2021}}</ref> Critics have called for a "forensic audit" to establish the cause of the increase.<ref>{{Cite web |date=August 25, 2017 |title=The Hard Reality Of Honolulu Rail Costs |url=http://www.civilbeat.org/2017/08/the-hard-reality-of-hart-costs/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170906134847/http://www.civilbeat.org/2017/08/the-hard-reality-of-hart-costs/ |archive-date=September 6, 2017 |access-date=September 6, 2017 |website=Honolulu Civil Beat}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=August 18, 2017 |title=City rail audit won't look for fraud? |url=http://www.grassrootinstitute.org/2017/08/city-rail-audit-wont-look-for-fraud/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170920141843/http://www.grassrootinstitute.org/2017/08/city-rail-audit-wont-look-for-fraud/ |archive-date=September 20, 2017 |access-date=September 20, 2017 |website=Grassroot Institute}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=August 15, 2017 |title=Rep Tupola Backs Forensic Audit for HART |url=http://www.hawaiifreepress.com/ArticlesMain/tabid/56/ID/20121/Rep-Tupola-Backs-Forensic-Audit-for-HART.aspx |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170920142812/http://www.hawaiifreepress.com/ArticlesMain/tabid/56/ID/20121/Rep-Tupola-Backs-Forensic-Audit-for-HART.aspx |archive-date=September 20, 2017 |access-date=September 20, 2017 |website=Hawai`i Free Press}}</ref> The tax increase legislation passed in 2017 also requires the State auditor carry out an audit of the project's accounts<ref name="Sep17Govsignsbill" /> and to consider alternatives for completing the system.<ref name="bringdowntoearth" /> The projected shortfall for the rail project is roughly $3&nbsp;billion, with the completion date pushed back to 2031.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Nakaso |first=Dan |date=March 11, 2021 |title=Honolulu Rail Project: $3B Deficit and No Recovery Plan |work=Governing |url=https://www.governing.com/community/honolulu-rail-project-3b-deficit-and-no-recovery-plan.html}}</ref>

===Initial General Excise Tax (GET) surcharge===
[[File:Mufi Hannemann.jpg|thumb|upright|Former Honolulu mayor [[Mufi Hannemann]].]]

After winning the 2004 election, Hannemann announced that construction of a rail line was an administration priority.<ref>{{Citation |last=Kua |first=Crystal |title=Director prioritizes rail transit |date=January 1, 2005 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2005/01/01/news/index5.html |work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |access-date=October 16, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100808174342/http://archives.starbulletin.com/2005/01/01/news/index5.html |url-status=live |archive-date=August 8, 2010}}</ref> The following May and upon prompting by the city, the [[Hawaii State Legislature]] passed a bill (Act 247) to allow counties a one-half percent increase in the Hawaiʻi General Excise Tax (GET), from 4% to 4.5%, to fund transportation projects. According to the bill, increased revenue would be delivered to counties implementing the raised tax to fund general public transportation infrastructure throughout Hawaiʻi, and to pay for mass transit in the case of the City and County of Honolulu.<ref>{{Citation |last=Kua |first=Crystal |title=City measure touts rail tax |date=May 5, 2005 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2005/05/05/news/index5.html |work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |access-date=October 16, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100808191819/http://archives.starbulletin.com/2005/05/05/news/index5.html |url-status=live |archive-date=August 8, 2010}}</ref><ref name="DoTax 2005-11">{{Citation |last=State of Hawaii Department of Taxation |title=State of Hawaii Department of Taxation Announcement 2005-11 |date=July 29, 2005 |url=http://www6.hawaii.gov/tax/announce/ann05-11.pdf |access-date=June 21, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091221190046/http://www6.hawaii.gov/tax/announce/ann05-11.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=December 21, 2009}}</ref> Money collected from the initial 4% GET would remain state revenue.

Republican governor [[Linda Lingle]] initially threatened to [[veto]] the bill, believing that money destined for county governments should be collected by the individual counties.<ref name="GET Success SB">{{Citation |last=Kua |first=Crystal |title=Late deal avoids transit veto |date=July 12, 2005 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2005/07/12/news/index1.html |work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |access-date=October 16, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100808200521/http://archives.starbulletin.com/2005/07/12/news/index1.html |url-status=live |archive-date=August 8, 2010}}</ref><ref name="Hawaii Reporter 1">{{Citation |last=Zimmerman |first=Malia |title=Surrounded By Democrats at the Capitol, Hawaii's Republican Governor Rescinds Decision to Veto Tax Increase Measure |date=July 12, 2005 |url=http://www.hawaiireporter.com/story.aspx?bd096a85-fe64-4e45-a053-17c14426d35e |work=Hawaii Reporter |access-date=October 16, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070809153228/http://www.hawaiireporter.com/story.aspx?bd096a85-fe64-4e45-a053-17c14426d35e |archive-date=August 9, 2007}}</ref> After compromising with legislative leaders and Mayor Hannemann, however, she allowed the bill to become law. On July 12, 2005, the bill was enacted as Act 247 of the Session Laws of Hawaiʻi 2005, without the Governor's signature.<ref name="DoTax 2005-11" /><ref name="GET Success SB" /><ref name="Hawaii Reporter 1" /><ref>{{Citation |last1=DePledge |first1=Derrick |title=Deal puts transit tax back on track |date=July 12, 2005 |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2005/Jul/12/ln/507120343.html |work=Honolulu Advertiser |page=A1 |access-date=July 7, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610040557/http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2005/Jul/12/ln/507120343.html |url-status=live |archive-date=June 10, 2011 |last2=Dingeman |first2=Robbie}}</ref> A month later, the [[Honolulu City Council]] authorized the one-half percent GET increase,<ref>{{Citation |last=Kua |first=Crystal |title=Transit project to raise taxes |date=August 11, 2005 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2005/08/11/news/index1.html |work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |access-date=October 16, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100808202610/http://archives.starbulletin.com/2005/08/11/news/index1.html |url-status=live |archive-date=August 8, 2010}}</ref> and Hannemann signed the measure into law on August 24.<ref>{{Citation |last=Kua |first=Crystal |title=Mayor signs tax, calls for multi-faceted traffic solutions |date=August 24, 2005 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2005/08/24/news/index7.html |work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |access-date=October 16, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100808203514/http://archives.starbulletin.com/2005/08/24/news/index7.html |url-status=live |archive-date=August 8, 2010}}</ref> Act 247 required Honolulu to use the funds only for the construction and operation of a mass transit system, and barred its use for public roads and other existing transit systems, such as [[TheBus (Honolulu)|TheBus]]. Since no other county authorized the excise tax increase before the deadline of December 31, 2005, the Hawaiʻi GET remains at 4% for the state's three other counties.<ref name="DoTax 2005-11" /><ref>{{Citation |last=Daranciang |first=Nelson |title=Excise tax increase begins tomorrow |date=December 31, 2006 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2006/12/31/news/story05.html |work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |access-date=February 2, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100808174132/http://archives.starbulletin.com/2006/12/31/news/story05.html |url-status=live |archive-date=August 8, 2010}}</ref> The increase went into effect on January 1, 2007, and was due to expire on December 31, 2022.<ref name="DoTax 2005-11" />

The Legislature considered a bill in the 2009 legislative session that would have redirected income from the half-percent increase back to the state to offset a $1.8&nbsp;billion projected shortfall in the following three fiscal years.<ref name="2009 GET">{{Citation |last=Wu |first=Nina |title=Legislature battles to avert $1.8B deficit |date=January 22, 2009 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/content/20090122_Legislature_battles_to_avert_18B_deficit |work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |access-date=July 7, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021164225/http://archives.starbulletin.com/content/20090122_Legislature_battles_to_avert_18B_deficit |url-status=live |archive-date=October 21, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |last1=DePledge |first1=Derrick |title=Governor emphasizes Hawaii's deficit woes as Legislature opens |date=June 21, 2009 |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2009/Jan/22/ln/hawaii901220369.html |work=Honolulu Advertiser |access-date=June 21, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101215024539/http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2009/Jan/22/ln/hawaii901220369.html |url-status=live |archive-date=December 15, 2010 |last2=Boylan |first2=Peter}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |last=Hawaii State Legislature |title=2009 Regular Session, Senate Bill 1626 Status |url=http://www.capitol.hawaii.gov/session2009/lists/measure_indiv.aspx?billtype=SB&billnumber=1626 |access-date=June 21, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090615111105/http://www.capitol.hawaii.gov/session2009/lists/measure_indiv.aspx?billtype=SB&billnumber=1626 |url-status=dead |archive-date=June 15, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |last=Hawaii State Legislature |title=Senate Bill 1626 Senate Draft 1, Relating to Taxation |url=http://www.capitol.hawaii.gov/session2009/Bills/SB1626_.HTM |access-date=June 21, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610135634/http://www.capitol.hawaii.gov/session2009/Bills/SB1626_.HTM |url-status=dead |archive-date=June 10, 2011}}</ref> The bill was opposed by Mayor Hannemann and other city leaders who believed that redirecting the money would jeopardize federal funding for the project,<ref>{{Citation |last=Nakaso |first=Dan |title=Stimulus could revive Honolulu, mayor says |date=January 24, 2009 |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2009/Jan/24/ln/hawaii901240322.html |work=Honolulu Advertiser |access-date=June 21, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101215031601/http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2009/Jan/24/ln/hawaii901240322.html |url-status=live |archive-date=December 15, 2010}}</ref> and was eventually dropped after U.S. Senator [[Daniel Inouye]] indicated to the Legislature that he shared the city's concerns.<ref>{{Citation |last=DePledge |first=Derrick |title=Legislature keeping its tax-raising options open |date=March 11, 2009 |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2009/Mar/11/ln/hawaii903110398.html |work=Honolulu Advertiser |access-date=June 21, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101215144029/http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2009/Mar/11/ln/hawaii903110398.html |url-status=live |archive-date=December 15, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |last=Borreca |first=Richard |title=Lawmakers fear revenue slump |date=March 11, 2009 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/content/20090311_Lawmakers_fear_revenue_slump |work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |access-date=July 7, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021164308/http://archives.starbulletin.com/content/20090311_Lawmakers_fear_revenue_slump |url-status=live |archive-date=October 21, 2012}}</ref>

===GET surcharge extensions and "Hotel Tax" surcharge===
In January 2016, the Council extended the GET for another five years to add $1.2&nbsp;billion in funding to cover a budget blowout. The council also required that the money raised by the extension go into a contingency fund and to pay for disability access to the system. HART was required to provide quarterly financial reports to the council.<ref>{{Cite web |date=January 28, 2016 |title=City Council approves tax surcharge extension for Honolulu rail project |url=http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/31076942/rail-tax-extension-approved |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170902143611/http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/31076942/rail-tax-extension-approved |archive-date=September 2, 2017 |access-date=September 2, 2017 |website=Hawaii News Now}}</ref>

On September 1, 2017, the Legislature, after meeting for a week in a special session on rail financing, approved further taxes to raise $2.4&nbsp;billion for the project. The taxes include a further three-year extension to the 0.5 percent General Excise Tax surcharge, which will now expire in 2030, and a thirteen-year, one percent surcharge on the existing 9.25 percent statewide Transient Accommodation Tax (TAT) which is charged to hotel guests. Efforts to pass a funding bill in May 2017 had failed and the impetus for the special session was an FTA deadline of September 15 for a funding plan to cover the shortfall.<ref name="Sep17taxespassed">{{Cite web |date=September 2, 2017 |title=$2.4 Billion Rescue Bill For Honolulu Rail Wins Final Approval |url=http://www.civilbeat.org/2017/09/2-4-rescue-bill-for-honolulu-rail-wins-final-approval/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170902021541/http://www.civilbeat.org/2017/09/2-4-rescue-bill-for-honolulu-rail-wins-final-approval/ |archive-date=September 2, 2017 |access-date=September 2, 2017 |website=[[Honolulu Civil Beat]]}}</ref> The bill also grants the state government oversight over the project including the appointment of two non-voting representatives on the HART board and calls for an audit of HART by the state auditor. It was signed into law by the governor on September 5.<ref name="Sep17Govsignsbill">{{Cite news |date=September 5, 2017 |title=Honolulu rail bailout becomes law with Ige's signature |work=Honolulu Star Advertiser |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2017/09/05/breaking-news/honolulu-rail-bailout-becomes-law-with-iges-signature/ |url-status=live |access-date=September 6, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170906034340/http://www.staradvertiser.com/2017/09/05/breaking-news/honolulu-rail-bailout-becomes-law-with-iges-signature/ |archive-date=September 6, 2017}}</ref>

===Federal Transit Administration's request for recovery plan===
In mid-2016, the FTA requested that HART develop a "recovery plan" by August 7, 2016. Also, in June, a separate report by Jacobs Engineering, the project management contractor, said under a worst-case scenario the final cost would be $10.79 billion.<ref name="Jacobsworstcase">{{Cite web |date=June 24, 2016 |title=New 'worst-case scenario' report reveals full 20-mile rail route could cost $10.79B |url=http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/32297303/new-worst-case-scenario-report-reveals-full-20-mile-rail-route-could-cost-1079b |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170906092222/http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/32297303/new-worst-case-scenario-report-reveals-full-20-mile-rail-route-could-cost-1079b |archive-date=September 6, 2017 |access-date=September 6, 2017 |website=Hawaii News Now}}</ref>

In January 2017, a group called "Salvage the Rail" published a plan, based on Option 2A from six alternatives proposed by the FTA to HART in 2016,<ref>{{Cite news |last=Ray Tsuchiyama |date=June 29, 2016 |title=A Rail System Option That Offers The Best Fit For Honolulu |publisher=[[Honolulu Civil Beat]] |url=http://www.civilbeat.org/2016/06/a-rail-system-option-that-offers-the-best-fit-for-honolulu/ |url-status=live |access-date=June 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160630203407/http://www.civilbeat.org/2016/06/a-rail-system-option-that-offers-the-best-fit-for-honolulu/ |archive-date=June 30, 2016}}</ref> that would terminate the elevated section at Middle Street and run at street level to the terminus along a route one block inland from the HART plan. The system would need to be reconfigured to use new driver-operated low floor vehicles, lowering the platforms on the stations already constructed.<ref>{{Cite web |date=February 7, 2017 |title=Salvage the Rail: Group renews call to bring rail to street level |url=http://www.kitv.com/story/34272479/salvage-the-rail-group-renews-call-to-bring-rail-to-street-level |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170928193248/http://www.kitv.com/story/34272479/salvage-the-rail-group-renews-call-to-bring-rail-to-street-level |archive-date=September 28, 2017 |access-date=September 28, 2017 |website=Island News KITV4}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=MODIFYING HONOULU AREA RAPID TRANSIT (HART) FOR STREET LEVEL OPERATION IN DOWNTOWN HONOLULU (January 2017) |url=http://www.salvagetherail.org/uploads/9/7/4/0/97405512/report_modifying_hart_for_street_level_operation_in_downtown_honolulu_january_2017_rev_feb_1.pdf |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170928150030/http://www.salvagetherail.org/uploads/9/7/4/0/97405512/report_modifying_hart_for_street_level_operation_in_downtown_honolulu_january_2017_rev_feb_1.pdf |archive-date=September 28, 2017 |access-date=September 28, 2017 |website=Salvage The Rail}}</ref> Proponents say it would save $3&nbsp;billion and four years of construction, as well as avoid disturbing burial sites under the downtown area.

After an extension was granted by the FTA, HART submitted its recovery plan in April 2017 which concluded that completion of the original 21 station route was the only viable option. An alternative "Plan B" to build only 14 stations within the already funded $6.5&nbsp;billion budget, was ruled out because of lower ridership, legal risks, insufficient contingency and other reasons. The new project cost was $8.165&nbsp;billion with media reports indicating that after financing charges are included it could be over $10 billion. An updated schedule for opening said the section from East Kapolei to Aloha Stadium will open at the end of 2020 and operation of the full route by December 2025.<ref name="HARTcommitted">{{Cite news |date=May 1, 2017 |title=HART committed to rail project's original route in recovery plan submitted to FTA |publisher=Pacific Business News |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/news/2017/05/01/hart-committed-to-rail-project-s-original-route-in.html |url-status=live |access-date=August 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170815182108/https://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/news/2017/05/01/hart-committed-to-rail-project-s-original-route-in.html |archive-date=August 15, 2017}}</ref><ref name="HARTrecoverplan">{{Cite web |date=April 28, 2017 |title=HART Recovery Plan |url=http://www.honolulutransit.org/media-center/news/498-hart-recovery-plan |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831140644/http://www.honolulutransit.org/media-center/news/498-hart-recovery-plan |archive-date=August 31, 2017 |access-date=August 15, 2017 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |format=PDF}}</ref>

In September 2017, HART submitted an updated recovery plan to the FTA with a new estimate price of $9.02&nbsp;billion. The plan still includes $8.165&nbsp;billion in construction costs, but has reduced financing costs of $858 million following state legislation granting both prolonged and new taxes to fund the project.<ref name="CostDropped1billion">{{Cite web |date=September 18, 2017 |title=The Estimated Cost Of Honolulu Rail Just Dropped By $1 Billion |url=http://www.civilbeat.org/2017/09/the-estimated-cost-of-honolulu-rail-just-dropped-by-1-billion/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170925132230/http://www.civilbeat.org/2017/09/the-estimated-cost-of-honolulu-rail-just-dropped-by-1-billion/ |archive-date=September 25, 2017 |access-date=September 25, 2017}}</ref> The State Auditor has been tasked to consider alternatives for completing the system, as part of its audit of HART.<ref name="bringdowntoearth">{{Cite web |date=September 27, 2017 |title=Bring Honolulu Rail Down To Earth |url=http://www.civilbeat.org/2017/09/bring-honolulu-rail-down-to-earth/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929043925/http://www.civilbeat.org/2017/09/bring-honolulu-rail-down-to-earth/ |archive-date=September 29, 2017 |access-date=September 28, 2017 |website=Honolulu Civic Beat}}</ref> As of January 2018 the FTA has not formally accepted the new recovery plan but has asked HART for more details including how it came up with its tax-revenue forecasts.<ref>{{Cite web |date=January 8, 2018 |title=Honolulu Rail Recovery Plan Remains A Work In Progress |url=http://www.civilbeat.org/2018/01/honolulu-rail-recovery-plan-remains-a-work-in-progress/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180111224002/http://www.civilbeat.org/2018/01/honolulu-rail-recovery-plan-remains-a-work-in-progress/ |archive-date=January 11, 2018 |access-date=January 11, 2018 |publisher=Honolulu Civil Beat}}</ref>

In February 2019, the FTA served HART with two subpoenas. The first asked the agency to send investigators documents relating to its real estate acquisition program. HART said some of the documents show it overspent on relocating residents and businesses along the rail route, which may have cost up to $4 million.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Feds serve Honolulu's rail agency with 2nd subpoena |url=http://www.metro-magazine.com/government-issues/news/733170/feds-serve-honolulu-s-rail-agency-with-2nd-subpoena?omdt=NL-MET-Express&omid=1000469379&ajs_uid=9453J3098134G9D&oly_enc_id=9453J3098134G9D&ajs_trait_oebid=3671F9146356B0M |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220429102508/https://www.metro-magazine.com/10031735/feds-serve-honolulus-rail-agency-with-2nd-subpoena?omdt=nl-met-express&omid=1000469379&ajs_uid=9453j3098134g9d&oly_enc_id=9453j3098134g9d&ajs_trait_oebid=3671f9146356b0m |archive-date=April 29, 2022 |access-date=July 3, 2019}}</ref> The second sought the minutes from all board of directors meetings from 2011 through 2018, including the board-members’ private discussions in executive sessions.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Honolulu rail project subpoenaed by feds for third time |url=http://www.metro-magazine.com/rail/news/733197/honolulu-rail-project-subpoenaed-by-feds-for-third-time?omdt=NL-MET-Express&omid=1000469379&ajs_uid=9453J3098134G9D&oly_enc_id=9453J3098134G9D&ajs_trait_oebid=3671F9146356B0M |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220429102502/https://www.metro-magazine.com/10031726/honolulu-rail-project-subpoenaed-by-feds-for-third-time?omdt=nl-met-express&omid=1000469379&ajs_uid=9453j3098134g9d&oly_enc_id=9453j3098134g9d&ajs_trait_oebid=3671f9146356b0m |archive-date=April 29, 2022 |access-date=July 3, 2019}}</ref>

In September 2019, the FTA accepted the recovery plan.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Dayton |first=Kevin |date=September 5, 2019 |title=FTA approves Honolulu rail recovery plan |work=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2019/09/05/breaking-news/fta-approves-honolulu-rail-recovery-plan/ |url-status=live |access-date=December 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191211210821/https://www.staradvertiser.com/2019/09/05/breaking-news/fta-approves-honolulu-rail-recovery-plan/ |archive-date=December 11, 2019}}</ref>

=== Revised schedule and estimates ===
An estimate released in November 2020 put the total cost of the project's construction and financing at $11 billion, and pushed back its expected completion date to 2033, with delays due to the [[COVID-19 pandemic]] and utility relocation work.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Honore |first=Marcel |date=2020-11-19 |title=City Pushes Rail's Opening To 2033, Price Tag Soars To $11 Billion |url=https://www.civilbeat.org/2020/11/city-pushes-rails-opening-to-2033-and-price-tag-soars-to-11-billion/ |access-date=2023-07-02 |website=[[Honolulu Civil Beat]]}}</ref> By March 2021, this had grown to $12.4 billion, with its estimated completion date moved forward to March 2031.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Honore |first=Marcel |date=2021-03-12 |title=Honolulu Rail Has A New Price Tag: $12.4 Billion |url=https://www.civilbeat.org/beat/honolulu-rail-has-a-new-price-tag-11-4-billion/ |access-date=2023-07-02 |website=[[Honolulu Civil Beat]]}}</ref><ref name="Mass Transit 2023-07-03">{{cite web|last=Wanek-Libman|first=Mischa|title=Honolulu's Skyline opens for service|date=July 3, 2023|work=Mass Transit|url=https://www.masstransitmag.com/rail/article/53065110/honolulus-skyline-opens-for-service|access-date=July 6, 2023}}</ref> Its construction constitutes Hawaiʻi's largest public works project ever.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Aquino |first1=Jamm |last2=Russell |first2=Cindy Ellen |date=2023-06-30 |title=Ridership commences on Honolulu's rail system |url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2023/06/30/photo-gallery/ridership-commences-on-honolulus-rail-system/ |access-date=2023-07-02 |website=[[Honolulu Star-Advertiser]]}}</ref>

==Route==
[[File:Honolulu Rail Project Groundbreaking Dignitaries 2011-02-22.jpg|thumb|right|City and state politicians at the project's groundbreaking ceremony.]]

Skyline consists of an almost entirely elevated [[rapid transit]] line from the eastern edge of [[Kapolei, Hawaii|Kapolei]], near the [[University of Hawaiʻi–West Oʻahu]] campus, to the [[Hawaii Capital Historic District|Hawaiʻi Capital Historic District]], with a future expansion planned to the [[Ala Moana Center]] (east of [[Downtown Honolulu]]). It will have twenty-one stations and run along the southern shore of [[Oʻahu]] between Kapolei and [[Honolulu]], passing through [[Waipahu, Hawaii|Waipahu]], [[Pearl City, Hawaii|Pearl City]], [[Waimalu, Hawaii|Waimalu]], [[ʻAiea, Hawaii|ʻAiea]], and [[Hālawa, Hawaii|Hālawa]]. The only at-grade trackage is a {{convert|0.6|mi|adj=on}} section near [[Leeward Community College]], which features no [[Level crossing|level crossings]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Sneider |first=Julie |date=August 2019 |title=Honolulu transit leaders eye late 2020 start to city's first passenger-rail system |agency=Progressive Railroading |url=https://www.progressiverailroading.com/passenger_rail/article/Honolulu-transit-leaders-eye-late-2020-start-to-citys-first-passenger-rail-system--58258 |url-status=live |access-date=December 17, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404080048/https://www.progressiverailroading.com/passenger_rail/article/Honolulu-transit-leaders-eye-late-2020-start-to-citys-first-passenger-rail-system--58258 |archive-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>

The full project is divided into four segments with overlapping construction periods and expected revenue service dates:<ref name="Sections" /><ref name="HARTConstruction">{{Cite web |title=Construction |url=https://honolulutransit.org/construction/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240615075208/https://honolulutransit.org/construction/ |archive-date=June 15, 2024 |access-date=June 15, 2024 |website=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation}}</ref>
# In 2016, the western portion of the line comprising ''Segment&nbsp;1'' ({{stn|Kualakaʻi}} to {{stn|Hālawa}}) was scheduled to open in late 2020, and the remaining segments ({{stn|Hālawa}} to {{stn|Kālia}}) in late 2025.<ref name="RailFAQ">{{Cite web |last=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transit |title=Rail Facts |url=http://honolulutransit.org/inform/rail-facts?catid=0 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161101155805/http://www.honolulutransit.org/inform/rail-facts?catid=0 |archive-date=November 1, 2016 |access-date=November 26, 2016}}</ref> In March 2021, this second date was pushed back to 2031.<ref name="hart2031">{{Cite web |date=March 10, 2021 |title=HART: Expect Honolulu's Full Rail Line To Be Done In 2031 |url=https://www.civilbeat.org/beat/hart-expect-honolulus-full-rail-line-to-be-built-by-2031/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210402035230/https://www.civilbeat.org/beat/hart-expect-honolulus-full-rail-line-to-be-built-by-2031/ |archive-date=April 2, 2021 |access-date=September 20, 2021 |work=Honolulu Civil Beat}}</ref> On May 9, 2023, it was announced that Segment&nbsp;1 would open the following month.<ref name="HNN 2023-05-09">{{Cite news |date=May 9, 2023 |title='A 21st century system': To fanfare, city announces official opening date of rail's first phase |url=https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/2023/05/10/city-announce-opening-date-first-phase-long-delayed-rail-project/ |access-date=May 10, 2023 |work=Hawaii News Now}}</ref>
# On March 18, 2025, it was announced that ''Segment&nbsp;2'' of service from [[Hālawa station|Hālawa]] to [[Kahauiki station|Kahauiki]] would open in October 2025.<ref name="segment2announce">{{Cite web |last=Huff |first=Daryl |date=2025-03-18 |title=Honolulu mayor delivers 5th State of the City address |url=https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/2025/03/19/live-honolulu-mayor-delivers-state-city-address/ |access-date=2025-03-18 |website=[[Hawaii News Now]]}}</ref> This is ahead of the previously estimated date of 2031,<ref name="Mass Transit 2023-07-03" /><ref name="HNN 2023-05-09" /> but behind the originally planned date of May 14, 2024.<ref name="energized">{{Cite web |last=Broder van Dyke |first=Michelle |date=June 14, 2024 |title=Second segment of Skyline will be energized |url=https://spectrumlocalnews.com/hi/hawaii/news/2024/06/14/second-segment-of-skyline-will-be-energized- |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240615075713/https://spectrumlocalnews.com/hi/hawaii/news/2024/06/14/second-segment-of-skyline-will-be-energized- |archive-date=June 15, 2024 |access-date=June 15, 2024 |website=Spectrum Local News}}</ref><ref name="HARTConstruction" />
# ''Segment&nbsp;3'' from [[Kahauiki station|Kahauiki]] to [[Kaʻākaukukui station|Kaʻākaukukui]] is still expected to open in 2031, with constructing beginning in August 2025.<ref name="segment2announce" /><ref>{{Cite web |last=Cervantes |first=Emily |date=August 11, 2025 |title=Phase 3 of Skyline Rail project breaks ground; what you need to know |url=https://www.khon2.com/wake-up-2day/phase-3-of-skyline-rail-project-breaks-ground-what-you-need-to-know/ |access-date=October 2, 2025 |website=KHON2}}</ref>
# The final two stations between [[Kaʻākaukukui station|Kaʻākaukukui]] and [[Kālia station|Kālia]] have been indefinitely deferred, although HART says it remains committed to completing them in the future.<ref name="faqs" />

