==Design==
===Segment 1: Farrington/Kamehameha===
On October 21, 2009, the city announced [[Kiewit Pacific Co.]] had won the $483&nbsp;million contract to build Segment&nbsp;1 of the line (the {{convert|7|mi|adj=on}} long Farrington and {{convert|4|mi|adj=on}} long Kamehameha sections), bidding $90&nbsp;million under the expected price. The stations were tendered separately.<ref name="RG 2009-10">{{Cite journal |date=October 26, 2009 |title=First contract awarded for Honolulu light rail |url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/single-view/view/10/first-contract-awarded-for-honolulu-light-rail.html |url-status=live |journal=[[Railway Gazette International]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091031081558/http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/single-view/view/10/first-contract-awarded-for-honolulu-light-rail.html |archive-date=October 31, 2009 |access-date=October 26, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |last=Hao |first=Sean |title=1st Honolulu Rail Contract Goes to Kiewit Pacific at $483M |date=October 22, 2009 |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2009/Oct/22/ln/hawaii910220359.html |work=Honolulu Advertiser |access-date=July 7, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610041439/http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2009/Oct/22/ln/hawaii910220359.html |url-status=live |archive-date=June 10, 2011}}</ref>

The construction of the rail line started from suburban areas in Kapolei and Ewa, and progresses east towards the urban center in Honolulu. There are 112 columns from [[Kualakaʻi station]] to the ʻEwa area.<ref>Tim Sakahara, "[http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/18452134/concrete-poured-on-honolulu-rail-project Concrete poured on Honolulu rail project] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200927065800/https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/18452134/concrete-poured-on-honolulu-rail-project/ |date=September 27, 2020}}," ''Hawaii News Now'', May 16, 2014, retrieved on October 29, 2014.</ref> The choice to start from Kapolei was made because Segment&nbsp;1 must include a baseyard for trains, which is more cheaply built away from the center, and also because the city chose to delay construction in the urban center to later segments of the project due to associated major impacts to existing infrastructure and unpopular traffic delays.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Hao |first=Sean |date=February 25, 2008 |title=First phase of rail would end in Pearl City |work=Honolulu Advertiser |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2008/Feb/25/ln/hawaii802250354.html |url-status=live |access-date=March 16, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080706013948/http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2008/Feb/25/ln/hawaii802250354.html |archive-date=July 6, 2008}}</ref>

To speed construction, the elevated trackway is built using [[precast concrete]] [[box girder]] [[Segmental bridge|bridge segments]].<ref name="Aspire15" /> This method was first used for [[MARTA]] in the 1980s.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Cox, William R. |date=Summer 2013 |title=Rail Transit Bridges |url=http://aspirebridge.com/magazine/2013Summer/SegTransit_Sum13_Web.pdf |url-status=live |magazine=ASPIRE: The Concrete Bridge Magazine |publisher=Precast/Prestressed Concrete Institute |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317230656/http://aspirebridge.com/magazine/2013Summer/SegTransit_Sum13_Web.pdf |archive-date=March 17, 2020 |access-date=December 19, 2019}}</ref> The trackway was designed by [[FIGG Bridge Engineers]] (responsible for the box girder segmental bridge) and [[HNTB]] (responsible for the columns). It is supported on single piers, each {{convert|6|to|7|ft}} in diameter at the base and {{convert|30|ft}} high, flaring at the top to support the lower section of the box girder; the piers are themselves supported by drilled shafts from {{convert|7|to|8|ft}} in diameter.<ref name="Aspire15">{{Cite magazine |last=Rodriguez, Jose |date=Summer 2015 |title=Honolulu Rail Transit Project (Segments 1 and 2) |url=http://www.aspirebridge.com/magazine/2015Summer/Project-HonoluluRailTransitProject.pdf |url-status=live |magazine=ASPIRE: The Concrete Bridge Magazine |publisher=Precast/Prestressed Concrete Institute |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201007223154/http://www.aspirebridge.com/magazine/2015Summer/Project-HonoluluRailTransitProject.pdf |archive-date=October 7, 2020 |access-date=December 19, 2019}}</ref>

Casting of the box girder segments began in 2014 at a rate of 13 segments per day; in total, 5,238 segments will be required for the first {{convert|10|mi|adj=on|abbr=on}} segment.<ref>{{Cite magazine |date=Fall 2014 |title=The Honolulu Rail Transit Project Honolulu, Hawaii – Construction Update |url=https://www.asbi-assoc.org/projects/project.cfm?articleID=3FB7A851-B3D3-C35F-B6CAB78D7E8F50A7&categoryIDs=44A57F74-F1F6-B13E-81940961706FF0A9 |url-status=live |magazine=Segments |publisher=American Segmental Bridge Institute |volume=59 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200801203413/https://www.asbi-assoc.org/projects/project.cfm?articleID=3FB7A851-B3D3-C35F-B6CAB78D7E8F50A7&categoryIDs=44A57F74-F1F6-B13E-81940961706FF0A9 |archive-date=August 1, 2020 |access-date=December 19, 2019}}</ref> The segments are cast locally in [[Kalaeloa, Hawaii|Kalaeloa]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Daysog, Rick |date=April 18, 2014 |title=Rail system's new concrete casting yard |url=https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/25280006/rail-systems-new-concrete-casting-yard/ |url-status=live |access-date=December 19, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219191455/https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/25280006/rail-systems-new-concrete-casting-yard/ |archive-date=December 19, 2019}}</ref> Each segment weighs {{convert|100000|lbs}} and measures (L×W×H, with length measured along the direction of the rails) {{convert|11|×|30|×|7|ft}},<ref name="CoC-presentation">{{Cite report |url=http://www.cochawaii.org/wp-content/uploads/Daniel-Grabauskas.pdf |title=Honolulu Rail Transit Project Update |date=June 25, 2014 |publisher=Honolulu Chamber of Commerce |access-date=December 19, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219203324/http://www.cochawaii.org/wp-content/uploads/Daniel-Grabauskas.pdf |archive-date=December 19, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> and the deck ranges in thickness from {{convert|8|to|15|in}}.<ref name="Aspire15" /> Once the piers were erected, a pier bracket ram was placed and a [[launching gantry]] was used to bridge the span between adjacent piers; a deck-mounted crane lifted the precast segments onto the gantry, which supported them while they were tensioned together.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Honolulu Rail Transit |url=http://somerseteng.com/project-gallery/honolulu-rail-transit/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219191453/http://somerseteng.com/project-gallery/honolulu-rail-transit/ |archive-date=December 19, 2019 |access-date=December 19, 2019 |publisher=Somerset Engineering}}</ref> In total, 430 of the 438 spans in Segment&nbsp;1 were assembled using precast box girder segments, at an average rate of 1 to 2 days per span.<ref name="Aspire15" />

For the eight long spans required to bridge the [[Interstate H-1|H-1]]/[[Interstate H-2|H-2]] Waiawa interchange in Pearl City, a balanced cantilever construction method was used instead. This covers the segments from Pier 252 to Pier 256.<ref name="CoC-presentation" /> Instead of precast segments, Kiewit used segments cast in-place, starting from the piers set in the freeway medians and working towards adjacent piers. The yellow-painted traveling forms at each end were used to cast each segment, then moved to the fresh end to cast the next segment. Each segment required {{convert|8000|lb}} of rebar and {{convert|48|cuyd}} of concrete, and weighed {{convert|210000|lb|abbr=on}}. 73 segments were required.<ref>{{youTube |id=Hums3p_LkjY |title=Time Lapse – Balanced Cantelevered Work over H1/H2 Merge}}</ref> The final pour for the balanced cantilever was performed in September 2016.<ref>{{Cite news |date=September 17, 2016 |title=Rail project's balanced cantilever work over H-1 in Pearl City finishing up |work=[[KHON-TV|KHON2]] |url=https://www.khon2.com/local-news/rail-projects-balanced-cantilever-work-over-h-1-in-pearl-city-finishing-up/ |url-status=live |access-date=December 19, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219203322/https://www.khon2.com/local-news/rail-projects-balanced-cantilever-work-over-h-1-in-pearl-city-finishing-up/ |archive-date=December 19, 2019}}</ref>

