===Segment 2: Airport===
[[File:The Rail outside of Pearl Harbor (47934029428).jpg|thumb|right|Airport section underway near [[Joint Base Pearl Harbor–Hickam]]. (2019)]]
[[File:Honolulu Rail Transit construction near airport.jpg|thumb|right|Project construction at [[Daniel K. Inouye International Airport]]. (2020)]]
The second segment of the route to be completed was the {{convert|5.1|mi|abbr=on|adj=on}} Airport section east from Aloha Stadium to Middle Street (the site of Kalihi Transit Center, an existing major bus transfer point). It includes four stations, including the [[Lelepaua station|Honolulu International Airport station]]. [[AECOM]] won the contract to design the Airport section in 2012 with a $38.8&nbsp;million bid.<ref>{{Cite press release |title=AECOM announced today that it had been awarded a US$38.8-million contract to design the airport segment of the Honolulu Rail transit Project in Hawaii. |date=January 27, 2012 |publisher=AECOM Technology Corporation |url=https://www.aecom.com/press-releases/aecom-announced-today-that-it-has-been-awarded-a-us38-8-million-contract-to-design-the-airport-segment-of-the-honolulu-rail-transit-project-in-hawaii/ |access-date=December 20, 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191220172249/https://www.aecom.com/press-releases/aecom-announced-today-that-it-has-been-awarded-a-us38-8-million-contract-to-design-the-airport-segment-of-the-honolulu-rail-transit-project-in-hawaii/ |archive-date=December 20, 2019}}</ref> The construction contract was awarded to the Shimmick-Traylor-[[Granite Construction|Granite]] Joint Venture (STGJV) in August 2016, who bid $874.8&nbsp;million;<ref>{{Cite news |last=Tobias, Lori |date=August 31, 2016 |title=Hawaii's $8B HART Project Is Chugging Along |work=Construction Equipment Guide |url=https://www.constructionequipmentguide.com/hawaiis-8b-hart-project-is-chugging-along/30535 |url-status=live |access-date=December 19, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219203323/https://www.constructionequipmentguide.com/hawaiis-8b-hart-project-is-chugging-along/30535 |archive-date=December 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Lincoln, Mileka |date=July 19, 2016 |title=Successful Airport-Middle Street rail segment bid totals $875M |work=Hawaii News Now |url=https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/32484731/hart-awards-airport-rail-construction-bid/ |url-status=live |access-date=December 20, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191220172246/https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/32484731/hart-awards-airport-rail-construction-bid/ |archive-date=December 20, 2019}}</ref> construction started in December 2016.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Parsons, Jim |date=September 13, 2017 |title=Funding Boost Shores Up Troubled Honolulu Rail Project |work=Engineering News-Record |url=https://www.enr.com/articles/42730-funding-boost-shores-up-troubled-honolulu-rail-project |url-status=live |access-date=December 19, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219191506/https://www.enr.com/articles/42730-funding-boost-shores-up-troubled-honolulu-rail-project |archive-date=December 19, 2019}}</ref>

The original design of the line forked it near [[Aloha Stadium]] into two routes, one passing South via Honolulu International Airport, and the other through Salt Lake, before reuniting at Middle Street in Kalihi. The city council initially decided to build the Salt Lake route before the airport route, as a result of horse-trading with City Councilmember [[Romy Cachola]], whose constituents included Salt Lake residents and whose vote was needed to pass the decision.<ref>{{Citation |last=Consillio |first=Kristen |title=Rail route changes trigger harsh words |date=November 17, 2008 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/content/20081117_rail_route_changes_trigger_harsh_words |work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |access-date=July 7, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021172735/http://archives.starbulletin.com/content/20081117_rail_route_changes_trigger_harsh_words |url-status=live |archive-date=October 21, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |last=Kua |first=Crystal |title=Rail Route to Go Via Salt Lake |date=February 22, 2007 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2007/02/22/news/story01.html |work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |access-date=January 18, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100504084933/http://archives.starbulletin.com/2007/02/22/news/story01.html |url-status=live |archive-date=May 4, 2010}}</ref> Soon after the city charter amendment on rail transit passed, the City Council reconsidered that decision, deciding to re-route the rail line to pass by [[Pearl Harbor]] and the airport and shelving the Salt Lake alignment as a future extension.<ref>{{Citation |last=Au |first=Laurie |title=New rail route OK'd |date=January 29, 2008 |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/content/20090129_New_rail_route_OKd |work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |access-date=July 7, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021172742/http://archives.starbulletin.com/content/20090129_New_rail_route_OKd |url-status=live |archive-date=October 21, 2012}}</ref><ref name="2009routechange">{{Citation |last=Hao |first=Sean |title=Council changes transit route to serve airport |date=January 29, 2009 |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2009/Jan/29/ln/hawaii901290352.html |work=Honolulu Advertiser |access-date=January 29, 2002 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101215042814/http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2009/Jan/29/ln/hawaii901290352.html |url-status=live |archive-date=December 15, 2010}}</ref> While increasing construction costs by 4%, the airport route is expected to bring significantly higher ridership, as it will ferry workers to both the airport and the [[Joint Base Pearl Harbor–Hickam|Pearl Harbor military base]] and shipyards.

The Airport section consists of 214 total spans. Like the earlier Farrington and Kamehameha sections, they are constructed using precast concrete box girder bridge segments, but for the Airport section, the segments are lifted and supported by an overhead [[gantry crane]] while they are tensioned.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation (HART) Airport Guideway & Stations |url=https://finleyengineeringgroup.com/projects/honolulu-authority-for-rapid-transportation-hart-airport-guideway-stations/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191220174447/https://finleyengineeringgroup.com/projects/honolulu-authority-for-rapid-transportation-hart-airport-guideway-stations/ |archive-date=December 20, 2019 |access-date=December 20, 2019 |publisher=Finley Engineering Group}}</ref> Both a conventional overhead gantry and an articulating gantry are being used during the guideway assembly.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Honolulu Rail Transit Project (HART) |url=https://mcnarybergeron.com/portfolio/honolulu-rail-transit-project-hart/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191220174447/https://mcnarybergeron.com/portfolio/honolulu-rail-transit-project-hart/ |archive-date=December 20, 2019 |access-date=December 20, 2019 |publisher=McNary Bergeron & Associates}}</ref> More than 2,700 precast segments are required for the Airport section, which also includes more than 230 columns for the piers and 5400 permanent [[sound wall]]s. For the pier foundations, shafts were drilled up to {{convert|350|ft}} deep,<ref>{{Cite web |title=Airport Guideway and Stations Design-Build Contrat |url=https://www.traylor.com/projects/airport-guideway-and-stations-design-build-contract/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191220174447/https://www.traylor.com/projects/airport-guideway-and-stations-design-build-contract/ |archive-date=December 20, 2019 |access-date=December 20, 2019 |publisher=Traylor Bros., Inc.}}</ref> including one excavated to {{convert|357|ft|4|in}} with a diameter of {{convert|10|ft}}. This was believed to have established a new record for a [[Deep foundation|drilled shaft]] [[Caisson (engineering)|caisson]]. The column, in Kalihi Stream on [[Kamehameha Highway]] between Middle Street and Puʻuhale Road, will be part of the support for [[Kahauiki station]].<ref>{{Cite press release |title=HART contractor drills largest, deepest column foundation to support the Honolulu Rail project |date=June 15, 2020 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-24108/HART%20News%20Release%20Record%20Drilled%20Column%20Foundation.pdf |access-date=January 7, 2021 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210109162657/http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-24108/HART%20News%20Release%20Record%20Drilled%20Column%20Foundation.pdf |archive-date=January 9, 2021}}</ref> Where the guideway contacts the supporting piers, custom bearings have been installed to accommodate movement ranging from {{convert|2|to|19|in}} and rotation of 0.015–0.03&nbsp;radians.<ref>{{Cite web |title=HART Airport Guideway and Stations Project – Honolulu, Hawaii |work=RJ Watson, Inc |url=https://www.rjwatson.com/Projects/hart-airport-guideway-disktron-bearing-installation/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191220174443/https://www.rjwatson.com/Projects/hart-airport-guideway-disktron-bearing-installation/ |archive-date=December 20, 2019 |access-date=December 20, 2019 |publisher=RJ Watson Inc}}</ref>

STGJV announced in December 2020 it had completed the last of the 2,708 precast concrete guideway segments for the Airport section, with this last segment scheduled to be installed over Ualena Street near Lagoon Drive in spring 2021. Each segment uses approximately {{convert|18|cuyd|abbr=on}} of concrete. Finished segment weights vary between {{cvt|80000|to|130000|lbs}} and have dimensions of {{convert|30.5|ft}} wide, {{convert|10.75|ft}} long, and either {{convert|8.5|or|4.5|ft}} high. The lower height is used in several places along the Airport section to accommodate overhead clearances and flight path restrictions.<ref>{{Cite press release |title=HART rail contractor reaches major milestone with completion of final precast segment |date=December 10, 2020 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-24394/HART%20Release%20(STG%20Builds%20Last%20AGS%20Segment%201112020%20AMG%20FINAL%20(002).pdf |access-date=December 30, 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210813221339/http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-24394/HART%20Release%20(STG%20Builds%20Last%20AGS%20Segment%201112020%20AMG%20FINAL%20(002).pdf |archive-date=August 13, 2021}}</ref>

=== Segment 3: City Center ===
[[File:Utility Relocations at the beginning of the Mauka Shift alignment of Skyline near the Kapalama Canal.png|thumb|right|Utility relocations on Dillingham Boulevard at the beginning of the Mauka Shift, near Kapalama Canal. The guideway will be built on the left of the equipment. (2025)]]Segment&nbsp;3 of the route to be completed will be the {{convert|3.3|mi|abbr=on|adj=on}} City Center section east from [[Kahauiki station|Kahauiki]] (Middle Street) station to [[Kaʻākaukukui station|Kaʻākaukukui]] (Civic Center) station. It includes six stations, including a [[Kuloloia station|downtown station]]. In August 2024, [[Parsons Corporation|Parsons]] and [[Tutor Perini]] who bid $1.66 billion; won bids for design and construction for the city center section respectively. The City Center section officially broke ground on August 13, 2025.<ref>{{Cite web |date=August 15, 2024 |title=Parsons (PSN) Secures Role in the $1.66B Honolulu Rail Project|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/money/topstocks/parsons-psn-secures-role-in-the-166b-honolulu-rail-project/ar-AA1pkeEH|access-date=August 26, 2024 |publisher=MSN}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=August 15, 2024 |title=HART announces $1.6B contract award for construction of next rail segment|url=https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/2024/08/15/hart-announces-16b-contract-award-construction-next-rail-segment/ |access-date=August 26, 2024 |publisher=Hawaii News Now}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last= |first= |date=2025-08-13 |title=Groundbreaking marks next phase of rail project into urban Honolulu |url=https://spectrumlocalnews.com/hi/hawaii/news/2025/08/13/groundbreaking-marks-next-phase-of-rail-project-into-urban-honolulu |access-date=2025-08-30 |website=Spectrum Local News |language=en}}</ref>

Originally the {{convert|3.3|mi|abbr=on|adj=on}} section terminating at [[Kaʻākaukukui station]], was supposed to be completed under a [[public-private partnership]] (PPP). It was estimated the City Center section will cost $1.6&nbsp;billion to complete.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Yoshioka, Wayne |date=May 14, 2018 |title=HART Looking For Private Partners to Complete Last $1.6B City Center Rail Segment |work=Hawaiʻi Public Radio |url=https://www.hawaiipublicradio.org/post/hart-looking-private-partners-complete-last-16b-city-center-rail-segment |url-status=live |access-date=December 20, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191220172255/https://www.hawaiipublicradio.org/post/hart-looking-private-partners-complete-last-16b-city-center-rail-segment |archive-date=December 20, 2019}}</ref> Under the proposed PPP, the City Center section would be procured under a design-build-finance-operate-maintain (DBFOM) contract, which would award the successful bidder the right to operate and maintain the entire system for a period of 25 years after completing the City Center section. The City of Honolulu would retain oversight over operations and maintenance, public information, and responsibility for fare vending and enforcement.<ref>{{Cite web |date=April 16, 2019 |title=Public-Private Partnership Development Program {{!}} Program Structure |url=https://honolulu.granicus.com/MetaViewer.php?view_id=3&clip_id=1000&meta_id=85914 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201005132659/https://honolulu.granicus.com/MetaViewer.php?view_id=3&clip_id=1000&meta_id=85914 |archive-date=October 5, 2020 |access-date=December 20, 2019 |publisher=Executive Matters and Legal Affairs Committee, City and County of Honolulu}}</ref> A contract for $400&nbsp;million to clear utilities in the City Center section was awarded in May 2018.<ref name="HSA-180507">{{Cite news |date=May 7, 2018 |title=HART awards $400 million contract to relocate utilities to make way for Honolulu rail |work=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2018/05/07/hawaii-news/hart-awards-400-million-contract-to-relocate-utilities-to-make-way-for-honolulu-rail/ |url-status=live |access-date=December 20, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191220174447/https://www.staradvertiser.com/2018/05/07/hawaii-news/hart-awards-400-million-contract-to-relocate-utilities-to-make-way-for-honolulu-rail/ |archive-date=December 20, 2019}}</ref>

HART issued a request for proposals (RFP) for the DBFOM contract for the City Center Guideway and Stations section in late 2018<ref>{{Cite press release |title=HART & city issue initial P3 request for proposals |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |url=https://honolulutransit.org/media-center/news/555-hart-city-issue-initial-p3-request-for-proposals |access-date=December 30, 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201022011346/https://www.honolulutransit.org/media-center/news/555-hart-city-issue-initial-p3-request-for-proposals |archive-date=October 22, 2020}}</ref> and announced it had received proposals from several bidders by July 2020.<ref>{{Cite press release |title=HART and city receive P-3 proposals |date=July 23, 2020 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-24111/HART%20RELEASE%20P3%20Offers%20Received.pdf |access-date=December 30, 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201019210530/http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-24111/HART%20RELEASE%20P3%20Offers%20Received.pdf |archive-date=October 19, 2020}}</ref> However, the bids for the construction of the City Center Guideway and Stations significantly exceeded HART's cost estimates, at $2.7&nbsp;billion compared to the $1.4&nbsp;billion estimate,<ref name="CB-2020-12-15">{{Cite news |last=Honore, Marcel |date=December 15, 2020 |title=HART, City Underestimated Cost Of Rail Work By $1.3 Billion, P3 Prices Show |work=Honolulu Civil Beat |url=https://www.civilbeat.org/2020/12/hart-city-underestimated-cost-of-rail-work-by-1-3-billion-p3-prices-show/ |url-status=live |access-date=December 30, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201230031447/https://www.civilbeat.org/2020/12/hart-city-underestimated-cost-of-rail-work-by-1-3-billion-p3-prices-show/ |archive-date=December 30, 2020}}</ref> and HART officially discontinued pursuing a PPP approach to completing the City Center section in November 2020.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Honore, Marcel |date=November 20, 2020 |title='How Do We Go Forward?' Honolulu Rail Leaders Kill P3, Confront Unknown Costs |work=Honolulu Civil Beat |url=https://www.civilbeat.org/2020/11/how-do-we-go-forward-honolulu-rail-leaders-kill-p3-confront-unknown-costs/ |url-status=live |access-date=December 30, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201230031427/https://www.civilbeat.org/2020/11/how-do-we-go-forward-honolulu-rail-leaders-kill-p3-confront-unknown-costs/ |archive-date=December 30, 2020}}</ref> The bids for the operation and maintenance portion of the contract (ranging from $4.2 to $5.3&nbsp;billion) were closer to the estimate ($4.95&nbsp;billion).<ref name="CB-2020-12-15" /> On December 14, 2020, HART issued a request for information, asking for input from the construction industry for the best way to structure a RFP that would receive realistic bids. It was expected that this contract will be awarded and subsequently, construction will begin for the six stations and guideway in August 2024.<ref>{{Cite press release |title=HART issues request for information for work to complete rail project construction |date=December 14, 2020 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-24608/HART%20RELEASE%20(CCGS%20PH%20RFI).pdf |access-date=December 30, 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210814140822/http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-24608/HART%20RELEASE%20(CCGS%20PH%20RFI).pdf |archive-date=August 14, 2021}}</ref>

In 2021, due to rising costs regarding the complexity of the City Center utility relocations; the original $400 million contract for clearing utilities signed back in 2018 was terminated and this section of utility relocations was divided into two contracts, one for utility relocations on Dillingham Blvd between [[Kahauiki station]] and [[Kūwili station]] as well as another for the city center between Kūwili station and Kaʻākaukukui station. In addition to this, the utility relocations were significantly rescoped to save costs.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Dayton |first=Kevin |date=June 26, 2023 |title=Honolulu Rail Spent $100 Million To Relocate Utilities. Much Of It May Have Been A Waste |url=https://www.civilbeat.org/2023/06/honolulu-rail-spent-100-million-to-relocate-utilities-much-of-it-may-have-been-a-waste/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240303191610/https://www.civilbeat.org/2023/06/honolulu-rail-spent-100-million-to-relocate-utilities-much-of-it-may-have-been-a-waste/ |archive-date=March 3, 2024 |access-date=June 15, 2024 |website=[[Honolulu Civil Beat]] |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Gutierrez |first=Ben |date=October 13, 2022 |title=Prep work for rail accelerates along Nimitz Highway |url=https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/2022/10/13/prep-work-rail-accelerates-along-nimitz-highway/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240303065454/https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/2022/10/13/prep-work-rail-accelerates-along-nimitz-highway/ |archive-date=March 3, 2024 |access-date=June 15, 2024 |website=[[Hawaii News Now]] |language=en}}</ref>

The significantly re-scoped utility relocations required modifying the original alignment in what was dubbed the "Mauka Shift".<ref>{{Cite web |title=Frequently Asked Questions |url=https://honolulutransit.org/faqs/ |access-date=2025-10-02 |website=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation}}</ref> This involved various column changes, along with a rerouting of the guideway due to the amount of electricity, water, sewer, and fiber optic utilities on the southern half of Dillingham Boulevard (between Waiakamilo Road and Kaʻaahi Street); as a result, the guideway location was changed from within the [[median strip]], instead moved [[wiktionary:mauka#English|''mauka'']] (inland) to the northern [[Shoulder (road)|shoulder]] of the roadway. Subsequently, [[Niuhelewai station]] was redesigned to reflect this shift. Utility relocations between Kahauiki station and Kūwili station are expected to be completed in mid-2026, with guideway construction starting in mid to late 2026. To relocate power lines under the deep Kapalama Canal as part of the Mauka Shift, contractors used [[microtunneling]] to dig three tunnels underneath the waterway.<ref>{{cite web |last=Tsai |first=Michael |date=2024-11-28 |title=Skyline expansion continues with microtunneling project |url=https://spectrumlocalnews.com/hi/hawaii/news/2024/11/28/skyline-expansion-continues-with-microtunneling-projec |access-date=2025-10-02 |website=Spectrum Local News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Tsai |first=Michael |date=October 12, 2022 |title=Work to start on rail's $496M 'mauka shift' along Dillingham |url=https://spectrumlocalnews.com/hi/hawaii/news/2022/10/12/work-to-start-on-rail-s--496m--mauka-shift--along-dillingham |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240302041657/https://spectrumlocalnews.com/hi/hawaii/news/2022/10/12/work-to-start-on-rail-s--496m--mauka-shift--along-dillingham |archive-date=March 2, 2024 |access-date=June 15, 2024 |website=Spectrum Local News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Dayton |first=Kevin |date=October 12, 2023 |title=Rail Changes Planned For Kakaako Mean Fewer Trees, More Buses |url=https://www.civilbeat.org/2023/10/rail-changes-planned-for-kakaako-mean-fewer-trees-more-buses/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240303065454/https://www.civilbeat.org/2023/10/rail-changes-planned-for-kakaako-mean-fewer-trees-more-buses/ |archive-date=March 3, 2024 |access-date=June 15, 2024 |website=[[Honolulu Civil Beat]]}}</ref>

The utility relocations between Kūwili station and Kaʻākaukukui station is expected to be completed in August&nbsp;2025, with guideway foundation construction beginning in September&nbsp;2025 near Kūwili station.{{Update inline|date=October 2025}} 

As of August 2025, preparations for guideway construction such as geotechnical borings, load testing, roadway preparation such as creating road closures is occurring throughout the route, as well as property acquisition and archeological digs on Halekuwila Street near the Kaʻākaukukui station is underway.<ref>{{cite web |date=2025-06-20 |title=HART Board of Directors Meeting Agenda |url=https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/sxxub40gt7k4lpm06ajvc/20250620-BOD-Agenda.pdf?rlkey=hn3iedwbmq2248jbmgjr3fbzu&e=1 |url-status= |archive-date= |access-date=2025-08-29 |website=Dropbox}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Consillio |first=Kristen |date=2025-08-18 |title=Honolulu rail project lane closures begin on Nimitz Highway |url=https://www.kitv.com/news/local/honolulu-rail-project-lane-closures-begin-on-nimitz-highway/article_74d5de3a-f993-4311-b983-c40cfbced172.html |access-date=2025-08-30 |website=[[KITV|KITV Island News]]}}</ref>

A formal [[groundbreaking]] ceremony occurred on August&nbsp;13, 2025 for load test foundations on the Civic Center station site.

[[File:Honolulu Rail Chinatown Load Test Foundations.jpg|thumb|Test foundations, built early in the CCGS contract, including a sample of station engravings for Hōlau station. These functioned as load tests for the precast girder-based guideway. As these require larger [[Capital (architecture)|capitals]] (caps on top of column) – compared to those for box girder sections – the capitals need to be separately installed. (2025)]]In order to lower costs, construction company [[Tutor Perini]]'s designs for this section differ from the earlier Farrington, Kamehameha, and Airport sections. Guideway construction will involve [[Girder bridge|concrete girders]] rather than [[Box girder bridge|precast concrete box girder bridge]] segments, resulting in the guideway being constructed by [[Crane (machine)|crawler cranes]] rather than [[Launching gantry|launching gantries]]. To save on maintenance costs, stations will abandon the use of fabric canopies, and instead use wood-clad steel canopies. Escalators will also be removed from all station plans, replaced by additional elevators. All stations will be constructed by their own sub-contractors. 

[[Hōlau station|Hōlau (Chinatown) station]] is planned to double as a public museum showcasing various artifacts found during utility relocations. The station will also be [[Mixed-use development|mixed-use]], with nearby abandoned building converted into retail and a plaza for food trucks.<ref>{{cite web | title=Director Lori Kahikina stops in to invite input on a special section of the Honolulu Rail project | website=[[YouTube]] | date=June 23, 2025 | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5eV9I9yZlD8}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Dropbox | url=https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/cb1y2kl9v7ajcel7m0yws/BOD-Chinatown-Station-Definitive-Design-Presentation.pdf?rlkey=od493xop8o3lito3g7nc5n7ti&e=1&st=9ez7fj58&dl=0}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Dropbox | url=https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/sxxub40gt7k4lpm06ajvc/20250620-BOD-Agenda.pdf?rlkey=hn3iedwbmq2248jbmgjr3fbzu&e=1}}</ref>

===Ala Moana extension===
[[Kūkuluaeʻo station|Kūkuluaeʻo (Kakaʻako)]] and [[Kālia station|Kālia (Ala Moana Center)]] stations were included in the original plan for Skyline but had to be eliminated from the initial segments of construction due to a severe funding shortfall. Despite the indefinite deferral, the Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation says it remains committed to completing these stations in the future. In 2024, [[Tutor Perini]] offered to do this section as a $325 million "add on" project to its city center construction contract after winning the bid for the rail construction between Middle Street and Civic Center.<ref>{{cite web | title=HART Reaches 'Huge Milestone' with Contract Award for City Center Guideway and 6 Stations | date=August 16, 2024 | url=https://www.civilbeat.org/2024/08/hart-reaches-huge-milestone-with-contract-award-for-city-center-guideway-and-6-stations/}}</ref><ref name="faqs">{{Cite web |title=FAQs |url=https://honolulutransit.org/faqs/ |access-date=June 21, 2023 |website=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |language=en-US}}</ref>

===Potential future extensions===
The long-term plan includes four additional extensions beyond [[Kūkuluaeʻo station|Kualakaʻi (East Kapolei)]] and [[Kālia station|Kālia (Ala Moana Center)]]. These include extensions East to [[University of Hawaiʻi at Mānoa]] and [[Waikiki|Waikīkī]], West to [[Kalaeloa, Hawaii|Kalaeloa]], and the link through [[Salt Lake, Hawaii|Salt Lake]] which was dropped from initial plans. None of these extensions are currently funded, but steps are being done in preserving alignments; especially in regards to ongoing projects planned on these alignments.<ref name="Map">City and County of Honolulu Department of Transportation Services, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/rail%20transit%20map%201.pdf Rail Transit Map (Part 1: Kapolei-Ewa)]{{dead link|date=January 2020|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/rail%20transit%20map%202.pdf (Part 2: Waipahu-Aiea)]{{dead link|date=January 2020|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/rail%20transit%20map%203.pdf (Part 3: Stadium-Kalihi)]{{dead link|date=January 2020|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}, [http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/rail%20transit%20map%204.pdf (Part 4: Kalihi-UH-Manoa/Waikiki)]{{dead link|date=January 2020|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}, retrieved January 5, 2009</ref><ref name="RG 2009-10" /><ref name="HART-extensions">{{Cite report |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/View/Collection-594 |title=Honolulu High-Capacity Transit Corridor Project: Final Environmental Impact Statement/Section 4(f) Evaluation |date=June 2010 |publisher=Department of Transportation Services, City and county of Honolulu |pages=2–48 |access-date=December 20, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191220162728/http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/View/Collection-594 |archive-date=December 20, 2019 |url-status=live |chapter-url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-16805/20110701-final-eis-chapter-02.pdf#page=48 |chapter=2: Alternatives Considered}}</ref>

====Extensions East past Kālia (Ala Moana)====
Past {{stn|Kālia}} ([[Ala Moana]]), the alignment travels to a station at the [[Hawaii Convention Center|Hawaiʻi Convention Center]], then splits into two branches – one to the [[University of Hawaiʻi at Mānoa]] campus and the other to [[Waikiki|Waikīkī]] on Kuhio Avenue.

In November 2017, the rail authority took a first step towards preserving a corridor for the extension to UH Mānoa.<ref name="ManoaExtension">{{Cite news |last=Kalani |first=Nanea |date=November 18, 2017 |title=Rail authority looks to preserve corridor for University of Hawaiʻi at Mānoa option |work=Honolulu Star Advertiser |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2017/11/18/hawaii-news/rail-authority-looks-to-preserve-corridor-for-uh-manoa-option/ |url-status=live |url-access=subscription |access-date=December 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213143008/http://www.staradvertiser.com/2017/11/18/hawaii-news/rail-authority-looks-to-preserve-corridor-for-uh-manoa-option/ |archive-date=December 13, 2017}}</ref>

In 2023, The City and County of Honolulu started preserving the Waikīkī alignment by installing [[TheBus (Honolulu)|bus]] lanes on Kūhiō Avenue that could eventually be used for future columns, in addition to a future transit-only Kūhiō Avenue.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.honolulu.gov/completestreets/waikiki | title=Complete Streets - Waikiki | date=February 6, 2024}}</ref> Later that year, work also began for the future UH Mānoa alignment by installing bike lanes on University Avenue, which will eventually be able to be used for the future rail utility relocations and columns between Mōʻiliʻili and UH Mānoa stations.<ref>{{cite web |date=August 26, 2025 |title=University and McCully – Honolulu Complete Streets |url=https://www.honolulu.gov/completestreets/university-and-mccully/ |access-date=October 2, 2025 |website=City and County of Honolulu}}</ref>

====Extensions past Kualakaʻi (East Kapolei)====
In addition to this; one extension is planned west from {{stn|Kualakaʻi}} (East [[Kapolei]]) to [[Kalaeloa, Hawaii|Kalaeloa]].

In 2021, The City and County of Honolulu has started planning to move the Kapolei Transit Center closer to the future Kalaeloa alignment.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Kapolei Maintenance Facility and Transit Center |url=https://www.honolulu.gov/rep/site/dts/dts_docs/Kapolei_Transit_Center_Project_Flyer.pdf |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240224203052/https://www.honolulu.gov/rep/site/dts/dts_docs/Kapolei_Transit_Center_Project_Flyer.pdf |archive-date=February 24, 2024 |access-date=June 15, 2024 |website=[[City and County of Honolulu]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Kaoplei Lots |url=https://www.honolulu.gov/rep/site/dlm/dlm_imgs/Kapolei_Lots.png |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211211011544/https://www.honolulu.gov/rep/site/dlm/dlm_imgs/Kapolei_Lots.png |archive-date=December 11, 2021 |access-date=June 15, 2024 |website=[[City and County of Honolulu]]}}</ref>

In June 2025, HART said that studies and preliminary planning for the future Kalaeloa alignment were underway, in the hopes of allowing it to be constructed at the same time as the Ala Moana extension.<ref>{{cite web | title=Spotlight Now: Rail executives share the latest on Honolulu's Skyline | date=June 17, 2025 | url=https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/2025/06/17/spotlight-now-rail-executives-share-latest-honolulus-skyline/ }}</ref>

====Salt Lake extension====
The link through [[Salt Lake, Hawaii|Salt Lake]] between {{stn|Hālawa}} (Aloha Stadium) and {{stn|Kahauiki}} (Middle Street) which was dropped from initial plans is being planned as an extension.

On April 29, 2021, Phase&nbsp;3 of the Salt Lake Boulevard Widening Project commenced. This is upgrading the final 2-lane part of Salt Lake Boulevard to 4 lanes. In addition to this, this project also makes this part of the Salt Lake corridor compatible for the future Salt Lake extension.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.saltlakewidening.com/post/phase-3-presentation-from-april-29-2021 | title=Phase 3 Presentation from April 29, 2021 | date=April 6, 2022}}</ref>

==Operations==
===Stations===
Local construction company Nan, Inc. won contracts to build six of the nine western stations in 2015; the West Oahu Station Group contract (for {{stn|Kualakaʻi}}, {{stn|Keoneʻae}}, and {{stn|Honouliuli}}) was worth $56.1 million,<ref>{{Cite press release |title=HART awards construction contract for West Oahu rail stations |date=July 16, 2015 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-18504/20150716-nr-hart-awards-construction-contract-for-west-oahu-rail-stations.pdf |access-date=December 20, 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200801184845/http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-18504/20150716-nr-hart-awards-construction-contract-for-west-oahu-rail-stations.pdf |archive-date=August 1, 2020}}</ref> and the Kamehameha Highway contract (for {{stn|Waiawa}}, {{stn|Kalauao}}, and {{stn|Hālawa}}) was worth $116&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Honoré |first=Marcel |date=December 23, 2015 |title=NAN Inc. wins deal for last trio of transit stations |work=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2015/12/23/hawaii-news/nan-inc-wins-deal-for-last-trio-of-transit-stations/ |url-status=live |url-access=subscription |access-date=December 20, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191220174453/https://www.staradvertiser.com/2015/12/23/hawaii-news/nan-inc-wins-deal-for-last-trio-of-transit-stations/ |archive-date=December 20, 2019}}</ref> The Farrington Highway Station Group contract (for {{stn|Hōʻaeʻae}}, {{stn|Pouhala}}, and {{stn|Hālaulani}}) was awarded in 2015 to Hawaiian Dredging for $79&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite web |date=June 10, 2015 |title=Farrington Highway Stations Group Construction Contract No. CT-HRT-1500236 |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-16596/20150610-fhsgcc-rfb-hrt-798316-award-letter.pdf |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217191033/http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-16596/20150610-fhsgcc-rfb-hrt-798316-award-letter.pdf |archive-date=February 17, 2017 |access-date=December 20, 2019}}</ref> STGJV was awarded the contract to build the four Airport section stations ({{stn|Makalapa}}, {{stn|Lelepaua}}, {{stn|Āhua}}, and {{stn|Kahauiki}}) as part of their $875&nbsp;million contract.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Mendoza, Jim |date=October 26, 2017 |title=It's coming: Rail work kicks off airport leg |work=Hawaii News Now |url=https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/2018/09/20/its-coming-rail-work-kicks-off-airport-leg/ |url-status=live |access-date=December 20, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191220213147/https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/2018/09/20/its-coming-rail-work-kicks-off-airport-leg/ |archive-date=December 20, 2019}}</ref> [[Tutor Perini]] was awarded the contract to build the six city center section stations ({{stn|Mokauea}}, {{stn|Niuhelewai}}, {{stn|Kūwili}}, {{stn|Hōlau}}, {{stn|Kuloloia}}, and {{stn|Kaʻākaukukui}}) as part of their $1.66 billion contract.<ref>{{Cite web |date=August 15, 2024 |title=HART announces $1.6B contract award for construction of next rail segment|url=https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/2024/08/15/hart-announces-16b-contract-award-construction-next-rail-segment/ |access-date=August 26, 2024 |publisher=Hawaii News Now}}</ref>

The Hawaiian Station Naming Working Group (HSNWG) was named by the Honolulu City Council in 2009 to develop [[Hawaiian language|Hawaiian]] names for each Skyline station.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Hawaiian Names for Rail Stations |url=http://honolulutransit.org/media-center/planning/528-hawaiian-names |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210921193157/https://honolulutransit.org/media-center/planning/528-hawaiian-names |archive-date=September 21, 2021 |access-date=July 2, 2023 |website=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation}}</ref> HSNWG proposed Hawaiian names for the nine rail stations on the [[Ewa District, Hawaii|ʻEwa]] end of the rail system in November 2017, and HART adopted the proposed names in February 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |date=November 22, 2017 |title=Hawaiian Station Naming Program |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-21439/20171122-hawaiian-station-naming-program.pdf |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200801170708/http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-21439/20171122-hawaiian-station-naming-program.pdf |archive-date=August 1, 2020 |access-date=December 19, 2019 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation}}</ref><ref>{{Cite press release |title=HART Board of Directors unanimously approve Hawaiian names for first nine rail stations |date=February 22, 2018 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-21921/HART%20New%20Release%20-%20Hawaiian%20Station%20Name%20Approval.pdf |access-date=December 19, 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200801170916/http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-21921/HART%20New%20Release%20-%20Hawaiian%20Station%20Name%20Approval.pdf |archive-date=August 1, 2020}}</ref> In April 2019, HSNWG recommended its names for the remaining 12 rail stations on the eastern end of the rail system, between Pearl Harbor and Ala Moana Center.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Wu, Nina |date=April 18, 2019 |title=Honolulu rail transit authority seeks feedback on Hawaiian names for train stations |work=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2019/04/18/hawaii-news/newswatch/honolulu-rail-transit-authority-seeks-feedback-on-hawaiian-names-for-train-stations/ |url-status=live |access-date=May 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190530022419/https://www.staradvertiser.com/2019/04/18/hawaii-news/newswatch/honolulu-rail-transit-authority-seeks-feedback-on-hawaiian-names-for-train-stations/ |archive-date=May 30, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite press release |title=Hawaiian names recommended for HART's rail stations |date=April 17, 2019 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-22715/HART%20Release%20(Station%20Hawaiian%20Names-Aloha%20Stadium%20to%20Ala%20Moana.pdf |access-date=December 19, 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317230657/http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-22715/HART%20Release%20%28Station%20Hawaiian%20Names-Aloha%20Stadium%20to%20Ala%20Moana.pdf |archive-date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>

All stations have restrooms that riders must ask a station attendant to unlock before using. They are described as being "secured access", in order to deter vandalism and improve the safety and security of stations, yet are "available for the public."<ref name="KHON20230616">{{Cite web |last=Boneza |first=Jenn |date=2023-06-16 |title=City cites safety, vandalism as reasons for excluding open public restrooms from Skyline |url=https://www.khon2.com/local-news/why-the-honolulus-rail-stations-will-not-have-bathrooms/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230711083702/https://www.khon2.com/local-news/why-the-honolulus-rail-stations-will-not-have-bathrooms/ |archive-date=2023-07-11 |access-date=2023-07-10 |website=[[KHON-TV|KHON2]]}}</ref>

