[[File:Skyline opening day.jpg|thumb|Passengers aboard Skyline on opening day. (2023)]]
When fully complete, Skyline trains are expected to carry more than 6,000 people per hour, with each train carrying over 300 passengers. That works to 20 trains per hour, or one train every three minutes.<!--The previous statement was that 20 trains would run per hour, an average 3 minute headway. The cited source states that each train can carry more than 300 passengers each, and more than 6,000 passengers will be carried per hour, which works out to 20 trains per hour via original research.--> Hours of operation were planned to be between 4&nbsp;a.m. and midnight.<ref name="qaa">{{Cite web |last=City and County of Honolulu Department of Transportation Services |title=Q&A: Honolulu Rail Transit |url=http://www.honolulutransit.org/library/files/honolulu%20rail%20transit%20brochure.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090117201255/http://www.honolulutransit.org/pdfs/QA_100808.pdf |archive-date=January 17, 2009 |access-date=January 5, 2009}}</ref><ref name="RailFAQ" /> In 2023, it was estimated that Segment&nbsp;1 would see 8,000 to 10,000 daily riders after one year of opening, that the opening of Segment&nbsp;2 (in 2025) would see see 25,000 daily riders, and that the opening of Segment&nbsp;3 (in 2031) would see 85,000 daily riders.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Nakas |date=2023-07-02 |title=Rail ridership projections, revenue uncertain after Skyline opens |url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2023/07/02/hawaii-news/rail-ridership-projections-revenue-uncertain-after-skyline-opens/ |access-date=2023-07-05 |website=[[Honolulu Star-Advertiser]] |page=A10 |language=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=May 10, 2023 |title=City to announce grand opening date for first phase of long-delayed rail project |url=https://www.facebook.com/HawaiiNewsNow/videos/city-to-announce-grand-opening-date-for-first-phase-of-long-delayed-rail-project/567216308855984/ |access-date=June 10, 2023 |website=[[Hawaii News Now]] |publisher=[[Facebook]]}}</ref> Upon opening a future extension to Ala Moana, Skyline is projected to serve an estimated 119,600 daily riders.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Bussewitz, Cathy |date=August 26, 2017 |title=Hawaii scrambles to keep train project from going off rails |work=AP News |url=https://apnews.com/94176bf9f55a41d2a272684dede9e8e0/Hawaii-scrambles-to-keep-train-project-from-going-off-rails |url-status=live |access-date=December 20, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191220220103/https://apnews.com/94176bf9f55a41d2a272684dede9e8e0/Hawaii-scrambles-to-keep-train-project-from-going-off-rails |archive-date=December 20, 2019}}</ref>

During its opening weekend, between 2&nbsp;p.m. on Friday, June&nbsp;30 and 7&nbsp;p.m. on Sunday, July&nbsp;2, 2023, Skyline saw 40,668 riders, equivalent to 1,564 passengers per service hour.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-07-05 |title=City announces initial Skyline ridership during free-fare period |url=https://www.honolulu.gov/transportation/news-releases/54162-city-announces-initial-skyline-ridership-during-free-fare-period.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230707081855/https://www.honolulu.gov/transportation/news-releases/54162-city-announces-initial-skyline-ridership-during-free-fare-period.html |archive-date=2023-07-07 |access-date=2023-07-06 |website=[[City and County of Honolulu]]}}</ref> During the first five days of service, which were [[Free public transport|fare-free]], Skyline saw a total of 71,722 passengers.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Mattos |first=Shelby |date=2023-07-05 |title=Nearly 72,000 passengers rode Skyline during its opening weekend |url=https://www.kitv.com/news/local/nearly-72-000-passengers-rode-skyline-during-its-opening-weekend/article_071f8b7a-1ba0-11ee-91e9-c3c4c186c6a7.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230706123018/https://www.kitv.com/news/local/nearly-72-000-passengers-rode-skyline-during-its-opening-weekend/article_071f8b7a-1ba0-11ee-91e9-c3c4c186c6a7.html |archive-date=2023-07-06 |access-date=2023-07-06 |website=[[KITV|KITV Island News]] |language=}}</ref>

In {{American transit ridership|annualdate}}, the line had an annual ridership of {{American transit ridership|HI Honolulu HR annual}},{{American transit ridership|annualcitation}} or about {{American transit ridership|HI Honolulu HR daily}} per weekday as of {{American transit ridership|dailydateasof}}.{{American transit ridership|dailycitation}} The month of October&nbsp;2024 saw a total of 109,430 riders, averaging 3,458 people per day, with an on-time performance rate of 99.5%.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-11-30 |title=Skyline Ridership Summary October 2024 |url=https://www8.honolulu.gov/dts/wp-content/uploads/sites/45/2024/11/Skyline-Ridership-October-2024.pdf |access-date=2025-03-18 |website=Honolulu Department of Transportation Services}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Skyline - Ridership |url=https://www8.honolulu.gov/dts/skyline-ridership/ |access-date=2024-10-31 |website=Honolulu Department of Transportation Services}}</ref>

Between July 1, 2024 and June 30, 2025, Skyline recorded a total of 1,204,341 trips.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Huff |first=Daryl |date=2025-07-05 |title=Honolulu rail project streamlines stations and tactics to save money |url=https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/2025/07/05/honolulu-rail-project-streamlines-stations-tactics-save-money/ |access-date=2025-09-26 |website=Hawaii News Now |language=en}}</ref> In October 2025, which saw the opening of Segment 2 to Middle Street, ridership for the month totaled 241,373, or 10,423 daily riders after the segment's opening,<ref>{{Cite web |title=Skyline Ridership October 2025 |url=https://www.honolulu.gov/dts/wp-content/uploads/sites/45/2025/11/Skyline-Ridership-October-2025.pdf |access-date=2025-11-11 |website=City and County of Honolulu Department of Transportation Services}}</ref> triple the ridership prior to the opening.
[[File:SkylineRidershipMay2026.png|center|thumb|600x600px|Honolulu Skyline ridership totals from September 2023 to May 2026<ref>[https://www.honolulu.gov/dts/skyline/ridership/ Honolulu Skyline ridership statistics]</ref>]]

===Fares===
Stations are equipped with [[Paid area|fare gates]] and [[Ticket machine|ticket vending machines]] (TVMs). Fares may be purchased by passengers and loaded onto [[HOLO card]]s, which also facilitate transfers to [[TheBus (Honolulu)|TheBus]], providing an unlimited number of free transfers for 2.5 hours after any boarding.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-06-19 |title=Skyline Rail Operations |url=https://www.honolulu.gov/transportation/divisions/mobility/rail-operations.html |access-date=2023-06-25 |website=City and County of Honolulu |archive-date=January 18, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240118064534/https://www.honolulu.gov/transportation/divisions/mobility/rail-operations.html |url-status=dead}}</ref> The base cost of an empty HOLO card is $2.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Fares & Passes |url=https://www.thebus.org/Fare/TheBusFares.asp |access-date=2023-06-25 |website=TheBus}}</ref> TVMs interfaces are available in English, [[Hawaiian language|Hawaiian]], [[Samoan language|Samoan]], [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]], [[Ilocano language|Ilocano]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]], [[Chinese language|Chinese]], and [[Korean language|Korean]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-06-29 |title=Riding Skyline Episode 2: Go Holo with your HOLO card |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TPZ3-R_Ew5o |website=Honolulu Department of Transportation Services |publisher=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>

Discounted fares are available to senior, youth, low-income, and disabled riders.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-09-22 |title=Fares |url=https://www.honolulu.gov/dts/fares/ |access-date=2025-09-27 |website=City and County of Honolulu Department of Transportation Services}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-07-31 |title=Low Income Transit Fare |url=https://www.honolulu.gov/dcs/litfp/ |access-date=2025-09-27 |website=City and County of Honolulu Department of Community Services}}</ref>

===Rail Operations Center===
[[File:Honolulu Rail Oahu Hawaii (50068478111).jpg|thumb|right|Honolulu Rail Transit guideway (2017), view directed west. The Train Wash Facility (TWF) is in the lower left.]]
The Rail Operations Center (ROC; also known as the Maintenance and Storage Facility) is the {{convert|43|acre|adj=on}} railyard, operations, and maintenance facility, located<!--{{coord|21.390694|-157.988123}}--> between the campuses of [[Leeward Community College]] and [[Waipahu High School]], just west of [[Hālaulani station]]. The design has been awarded [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED]] Silver certification.<ref name="SRG">{{Cite web |title=Honolulu Rail Transit Project: System Resource Guide |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-21774/20180511-hrtp-system-resource-guide.pdf#page=9 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200802010108/http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-21774/20180511-hrtp-system-resource-guide.pdf#page=9 |archive-date=August 2, 2020 |access-date=December 19, 2019 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation}}</ref>

The four buildings on the ROC campus are:
*Operation & Servicing Building (OSB) – Housing primary vehicle maintenance facilities and the Operations and Control Center, where operators will monitor and control vehicle movement
*Maintenance of Way Building (MOW) – Housing equipment used to inspect and repair tracks
*Train Wash Facility (TWF) – An automated facility to clean vehicle exteriors
*Wheel Truing Building (WTB) – A maintenance facility for vehicle wheels

The contract for the ROC was awarded to the Kiewit/Kobayashi Joint Venture in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web |date=June 30, 2011 |title=Agreement for Design-Build Services, Contract No. CT-DTS-1000449 |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-16112/MSF-Contract%20Package-10A0449.pdf |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200801191434/http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-16112/MSF-Contract%20Package-10A0449.pdf |archive-date=August 1, 2020 |access-date=December 23, 2019 |publisher=Honolulu High-Capacity Transit Corridor Project}}</ref> The contract was initially awarded at a cost of $195&nbsp;million; when the ROC was completed in July 2016, the actual incurred costs were $274&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite report |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-19156/201607-monthly-progress-report-low-res.pdf |title=Honolulu Rail Transit Project Monthly Progress Report |date=July 2016 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |access-date=December 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200801203412/http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-19156/201607-monthly-progress-report-low-res.pdf |archive-date=August 1, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>{{rp|39}}

===Rolling stock===
[[File:Honolulu Rail Transit First Trainset 2017-02-18.jpg|thumb|right|First trainset on public display in February 2017.]]
{{See also|Hitachi Rail Italy Driverless Metro}}

Although several other technologies were considered, including technologies commonly used for airport [[people mover]] systems like rubber tires, maglev, [[Funicular|cable-hauled]], and monorail, then-mayor Mufi Hannemann strongly believed in "steel on steel" construction, saying "I will not put this city in a position of financial disaster […] If it's not 'steel on steel,' I'll pull the plug."<ref>{{Cite web |date=April 18, 2008 |title=Hannemann: If It's Not Steel on Steel, I'll Pull the Plug |url=https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/8191239/hannemann-if-its-not-steel-on-steel-ill-pull-the-plug |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220429102500/https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/8191239/hannemann-if-its-not-steel-on-steel-ill-pull-the-plug/ |archive-date=April 29, 2022 |access-date=April 22, 2022 |website=www.hawaiinewsnow.com |language=en}}</ref> The line uses {{convert|256|ft|m|abbr=on|adj=on}} four-car train sets, each with the capacity to carry nearly 800 passengers,<ref name="railwayage">{{Cite web |last=Vantuono |first=William C. |date=2023-06-30 |title='Skyline' Opens in Honolulu |url=https://www.railwayage.com/passenger/rapid-transit/skyline-opens-in-honolulu/ |access-date=2023-07-02 |website=[[Railway Age]]}}</ref> similar in weight to [[heavy rail]] systems elsewhere in the United States (such as the [[Chicago 'L']] in [[Chicago, Illinois]]). Physically, the Honolulu system resembles light rapid transit systems such as New Taipei's [[Circular line (Taipei metropolitan area)|Circular Line]] which uses the same technology, Vancouver's [[SkyTrain (Vancouver)|SkyTrain]], the [[Copenhagen Metro]], and the [[Docklands Light Railway]] in London, but is legally classified as a heavy rail system.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.transit.dot.gov/sites/fta.dot.gov/files/2021-09/Rail-Safety-Data-Report-2007-2018-09-23-2021.pdf |title=RAIL SAFETY DATA REPORT |publisher=[[Federal Transit Administration]] |date=2021-09-01 |access-date=2024-07-17}}</ref> The system is the first in the U.S. (outside of airport [[people mover]] systems) to feature [[Platform screen doors#Types|platform gates]] in conjunction with [[Automatic train operation|driverless operation]].<ref name="station-design-offi">{{Cite web |title=Home |url=http://www.honolulutransit.org/rail-system-guide/station-design-and-features.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140728211528/http://www.honolulutransit.org/rail-system-guide/station-design-and-features.aspx |archive-date=July 28, 2014 |access-date=September 30, 2014 |website=honolulutransit.org}}</ref> Rolling stock for the line includes 80 cars in 20 four-car train sets.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Train Vehicle Fact Sheet |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-17047/20140218-hart-train-vehicle-fact-sheet.pdf |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220731222025/http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-17047/20140218-hart-train-vehicle-fact-sheet.pdf |archive-date=July 31, 2022}}</ref> Each car is {{convert|64|ft|m|abbr=on|adj=on}} long, weighs {{convert|72,000|lb|kg|sigfig=2|abbr=on|adj=on}}, and has 36 seats with a listed total capacity of 195 people, and sits on [[Standard-gauge railway|standard-gauge]] (1,435&nbsp;mm) rails.<ref name="Rolling Stock 2011">{{Citation |last=Park |first=Gene |title=Have a seat |date=March 22, 2011 |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110322_Have_a_seat.html |work=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |volume=130 |issue=50 |page=A1, A6 |access-date=March 22, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808010159/http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110322_Have_a_seat.html |url-status=live |archive-date=August 8, 2014}}</ref><ref name="railwayage" /> The cars are powered by a [[third rail]] electrification system, delivering [[List of railway electrification systems#Top contact|750 V DC]].<ref>{{Citation |last1=U.S. Department of Transportation Federal Transit Administration |title=Honolulu High-Capacity Transit Corridor Project Final Environmental Impact Statement/Section 4(f) Evaluation |date=June 2010 |url=http://honolulutransit.org/library/files/02.pdf |pages=2–30 |access-date=March 28, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170902144623/http://honolulutransit.org/library/files/02.pdf |url-status=live |archive-date=September 2, 2017 |last2=City and County of Honolulu Department of Transportation Services}}</ref>

====Contract and delivery====
The contract for railcars (named the Core Systems Design-Build-Operate-Maintain Services contract) was signed on November 28, 2011, with a joint venture between [[Hitachi Rail Italy]] (then known as AnsaldoBreda) and [[Hitachi Rail STS]] (then known as Ansaldo STS).<ref name="CT-DTS-1100194">{{Cite web |date=November 28, 2011 |title=Agreement for Design-Build-Operate-Maintain Services, Contract No. CT-DTS-1100194 |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-14729/Agreement.pdf |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170210003020/http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-14729/Agreement.pdf |archive-date=February 10, 2017 |access-date=December 23, 2019 |publisher=Honolulu High-Capacity Transit Corridor Project}}</ref> The companies previously collaborated on the construction and operation of vehicles for the [[Copenhagen Metro]]<ref>{{Citation |last=Brown |first=Robert |title=Fact Check — Carlisle: Ansaldo's Copenhagen Line One of World's Best |date=April 15, 2011 |url=http://www.civilbeat.com/fact_checks/2011/04/15/10342-fact-check-carlisle-ansaldos-copenhagen-line-one-of-worlds-best/ |work=Honolulu Civil Beat |access-date=April 16, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722225537/http://www.civilbeat.com/fact_checks/2011/04/15/10342-fact-check-carlisle-ansaldos-copenhagen-line-one-of-worlds-best/ |url-status=live |publisher=Peer News LLC |archive-date=July 22, 2011}}</ref> and the [[Brescia Metro]]. Both companies were later purchased by [[Hitachi Rail|Hitachi]] in 2015<ref>{{Cite news |date=February 24, 2015 |title=Hitachi agrees to buy Ansaldo STS and AnsaldoBreda |work=Railway Gazette |url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/business/single-view/view/hitachi-agrees-to-buy-ansaldo-sts-and-ansaldobreda.html |url-status=live |access-date=February 25, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201101165012/https://www.railwaygazette.com/news/business/single-view/view/hitachi-agrees-to-buy-ansaldo-sts-and-ansaldobreda.html |archive-date=November 1, 2020}}</ref> and the Ansaldo Honolulu Joint Venture was renamed to Hitachi Rail Honolulu (HRH).

Under the $1.1&nbsp;billion contract, HRH is responsible for designing and fabricating railcars ($574&nbsp;million), pre-revenue testing to validate train performance ($167&nbsp;million), and operations and maintenance (O&M) during the first five years of revenue service ($339&nbsp;million). There is an option to continue O&M services for HART for an additional five years ($318&nbsp;million).<ref name="CT-DTS-1100194" />

The two unsuccessful bidders for the railcar contract, [[Bombardier Transportation|Bombardier]] and [[Sumitomo Corporation|Sumitomo]], filed protests over the award.<ref>{{Citation |last=Park |first=Gene |title=2 bidders protest city's rail decision |date=April 12, 2011 |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110412_2_bidders_protest_citys_rail_decision.html |work=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |volume=130 |issue=71 |access-date=April 12, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120919231707/http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110412_2_bidders_protest_citys_rail_decision.html |url-status=live |archive-date=September 19, 2012}}</ref> Both protests were rejected during the administrative process, but Bombardier sought judicial review of their protest.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Kalani |first=Nanea |date=October 14, 2011 |title=Disqualified Honolulu Rail Bidder Bombardier Files New Appeal |work=Honolulu Civil Beat |publisher=Peer News |url=http://www.civilbeat.com/articles/2011/10/14/13270-disqualified-honolulu-rail-bidder-bombardier-files-new-appeal/ |url-status=live |access-date=July 13, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130807094157/http://www.civilbeat.com/articles/2011/10/14/13270-disqualified-honolulu-rail-bidder-bombardier-files-new-appeal/ |archive-date=August 7, 2013}}</ref> The decision against Bombardier's protest was affirmed by both the state Circuit Court and the Intermediate Court of Appeals.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Abramson |first=Mark |date=October 17, 2012 |title=Hawaii Appeals Court upholds ruling in Bombardier rail lawsuit |work=Pacific Business News |publisher=American City Business Journals |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/news/2012/10/17/hawaii-appeals-court-upholds-ruling-in.html |url-status=live |access-date=July 13, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019155559/http://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/news/2012/10/17/hawaii-appeals-court-upholds-ruling-in.html |url-access=subscription |archive-date=October 19, 2012}}</ref><ref>''[http://www.courts.state.hi.us/docs/opin_ord/ica/2012/oct/CAAP-11-0000756.pdf Bombardier Transportation (Holdings) USA Inc. v. Director, Department of Budget and Fiscal Services, City and County of Honolulu] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024013745/http://www.courts.state.hi.us/docs/opin_ord/ica/2012/oct/CAAP-11-0000756.pdf |date=October 24, 2012}}'', 128 Haw. 413 (App.), {{West |P|289|3|1049|Haw. App.|2012|}}</ref>

The first two cars arrived in Hawaiʻi in March&nbsp;2016,<ref name="IRJ-1603">{{Cite news |last=Barrow, Keith |date=March 29, 2016 |title=First Honolulu metro cars delivered |work=International Railway Journal |url=https://www.railjournal.com/passenger/metros/first-honolulu-metro-trains-delivered/ |url-status=live |access-date=December 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223201648/https://www.railjournal.com/passenger/metros/first-honolulu-metro-trains-delivered/ |archive-date=December 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Honoré, Marcel |date=March 24, 2016 |title=First train cars arrive in Honolulu for rail transit project |work=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2016/03/24/business/business-breaking/first-train-cars-arrive-in-honolulu-for-rail-transit-project/ |url-status=live |access-date=December 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223200146/https://www.staradvertiser.com/2016/03/24/business/business-breaking/first-train-cars-arrive-in-honolulu-for-rail-transit-project/ |archive-date=December 23, 2019}}</ref> and the first train was unveiled to the public at the Rail Operations Center on May 2, 2016.<ref>{{Cite press release |title=Honolulu Gets First Look at New Transit System Rail Cars |date=May 2, 2016 |publisher=Hitachi USA |url=http://www.hitachi.us/press/honolulu-new-transit-system-rail-cars |access-date=December 23, 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223200154/http://www.hitachi.us/press/honolulu-new-transit-system-rail-cars |archive-date=December 23, 2019}}</ref> To meet "[[Buy America Act|Buy America]]" requirements for federally-funded transit projects, the bodyshells are fabricated at the Hitachi Rail Italy plant in [[Reggio Calabria, Italy]], then shipped to Hitachi Rail's plant in [[Pittsburg, California]] for final assembly.<ref name="IRJ-1603" />

In December 2016, Hitachi Rail Italy reported defects were discovered in the welds in the extruded aluminum beams of twenty-seven car shells, four of which were already in Hawaiʻi. The manufacturer will fix the problems, but warned delivery may be delayed as production of new vehicles will be halted.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Honoré, Marcel |date=December 16, 2016 |title=New defect could further stall rail |work=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |url=https://www.pressreader.com/usa/honolulu-star-advertiser/20161216/281479276058340 |url-status=live |access-date=September 8, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170908111129/https://www.pressreader.com/usa/honolulu-star-advertiser/20161216/281479276058340 |archive-date=September 8, 2017}}</ref> In March 2017, HART said they would meet the interim opening needs after repair of the defective cars and that full opening would not be affected.<ref>{{Cite web |date=February 18, 2017 |title=Repairs to fix rail-car production defects scheduled to start in March |url=http://khon2.com/2017/02/18/repairs-to-fix-rail-car-production-defects-scheduled-to-start-in-march/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170908112644/http://khon2.com/2017/02/18/repairs-to-fix-rail-car-production-defects-scheduled-to-start-in-march/ |archive-date=September 8, 2017 |access-date=September 8, 2017 |website=[[KHON-TV|KHON2]]}}</ref>

In May 2017, trains were towed on tracks in Honolulu for the first time to check clearances.<ref>{{Cite web |date=May 30, 2017 |title=Honolulu tests rail car on track for first time |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2017/05/30/breaking-news/hart-train-makes-first-appearance-on-guideway/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170908112339/http://www.staradvertiser.com/2017/05/30/breaking-news/hart-train-makes-first-appearance-on-guideway/ |archive-date=September 8, 2017 |access-date=September 8, 2017 |website=Honolulu Star-Advertiser}}</ref> Testing of trains under their own power commenced in October 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Gutierrez |first1=Ben |date=October 19, 2017 |title=In successful test, city rail cars reach 40 mph on its own power |url=http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/36632259/city-rail-cars-reach-40-mph-in-speed-test |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020135507/http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/36632259/city-rail-cars-reach-40-mph-in-speed-test |archive-date=October 20, 2017 |access-date=October 20, 2017 |website=Hawaii News Now}}</ref>

== Timeline of progress ==
{{Prose|section|date=June 2024}}
*February 2006 – A draft transportation plan includes $2.5&nbsp;billion for a fixed-rail system between Kapolei and Mānoa.<ref>{{Cite web |title=StarBulletin.com {{!}} News {{!}} /2006/02/19/ |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2006/02/19/news/story03.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201004234438/http://archives.starbulletin.com/2006/02/19/news/story03.html |archive-date=October 4, 2020 |access-date=September 10, 2020 |website=archives.starbulletin.com}}</ref>
*June 2006 – Officials estimate the infrastructure construction cost at estimated at $3&nbsp;billion, $200&nbsp;million more than a previous estimate, for a 24-mile system. This does not include the cost of the trains.<ref name="2006cost3billion">{{Cite web |date=June 23, 2006 |title=Rail transit system cost estimate: $3 billion |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2006/Jun/23/ln/FP606230364.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170901155547/http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2006/Jun/23/ln/FP606230364.html |archive-date=September 1, 2017 |access-date=September 1, 2017 |publisher=Honolulu Advertiser}}</ref>
*January 2007 – The General Excise Tax (GET) within the City and County of Honolulu is increased by 0.5% with the extra funds earmarked for a mass transit system. The increase was set to expire on December 31, 2022.
*February 2007 – The City Council approves the Minimum Operating Segment from East Kapolei to Ala Moana Center, via Salt Lake Boulevard.<ref name="HARTrecoverplan" />
*October 2008 – The Draft Environmental Impact Statement (DEIS) is released to the public. The projected cost is $3.7&nbsp;billion including $1&nbsp;billion for contingencies.<ref>{{Cite web |date=October 12, 2008 |title=Just the facts on Honolulu transit |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2008/Oct/12/ln/hawaii810120332.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170901201609/http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2008/Oct/12/ln/hawaii810120332.html |archive-date=September 1, 2017 |access-date=September 1, 2017}}</ref>
*November 2008 – Fifty-three percent of voters support measures to give the Honolulu City Council authority to proceed with "establishment of a steel wheel on steel rail transit system". The estimated cost is $4&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Council OKs ballot question on transit |work=Honolulu Star Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/08/21/news/story02.html |url-status=live |access-date=September 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090924041556/http://archives.starbulletin.com/2008/08/21/news/story02.html |archive-date=September 24, 2009}}</ref>
*January 2009 – The middle portion of the route between Aloha Stadium and Middle Street is amended to have stations at the Pearl Harbor Naval Base and the Honolulu Airport which had one of the original options. The previous route followed Salt Lake Boulevard.<ref name="2009routechange" />
*June 2010 – The Final Environmental Impact Statement (FEIS) is released to the public. Estimated cost is $5.5&nbsp;billion. Patronage by 2030 is projected to be 116,300 riders per day.<ref>{{Cite web |date=June 16, 2010 |title=Honolulu Rail: The Complete Final Environmental Impact Statement |url=http://www.civilbeat.org/2010/06/2009-honolulu-rail-the-complete-final-environmental-impact-statement/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170901201411/http://www.civilbeat.org/2010/06/2009-honolulu-rail-the-complete-final-environmental-impact-statement/ |archive-date=September 1, 2017 |access-date=September 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |last=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transit |title=System Figures |url=http://honolulutransit.org/rail-system-guide/facts-and-figures.aspx |work=honolulutransit.org |access-date=July 22, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140729021514/http://www.honolulutransit.org/rail-system-guide/facts-and-figures.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 29, 2014}}</ref>
*December 2010 – A report, commissioned by outgoing Governor Lingle, is released which warns the project could cost at least $1.7&nbsp;billion more than the city's projected $5.5&nbsp;billion price tag.<ref name="LingleReport2010" />
*March 2012 – Dan Grabauskas becomes executive director and CEO of HART on a three-year contract. He takes his position in April 2012.<ref name="HonoluluGov2012-03-01" /><ref name="KHON2016-08-16">{{Cite news |last=Kuriowa |first=Jared |date=August 18, 2016 |title=HART CEO Grabauskas resigns, Formby steps in as interim |work=[[KHON-TV|KHON2]] |location=[[Honolulu]] |url=https://www.khon2.com/news/local-news/hart-ceo-dan-grabauskas-resigns/1025883209 |access-date=January 11, 2019}}{{dead link|date=June 2022|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>
*May 2012 – Construction workers started pouring concrete on the foundations that will hold the rail columns.<ref>Tim Sakahara, "[http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/18452134/concrete-poured-on-honolulu-rail-project Concrete poured on Honolulu rail project] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200927065800/https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/18452134/concrete-poured-on-honolulu-rail-project/ |date=September 27, 2020}}," ''Hawaii News Now'', May 16, 2012, retrieved on October 29, 2014.</ref>
*December 2012 – Honolulu City Council and the Federal Transit Authority (FTA) sign agreement for the project with a budget of $5.12&nbsp;billion including $1.55&nbsp;billion provided by the Federal Government. Full system revenue service is projected for January 31, 2020.<ref name="HartRecoveryPlan2017">{{Cite web |date=April 28, 2017 |title=HART Recovery Plan |url=http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-20510/20170428-hart-recovery-plan.pdf |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831174918/http://hartdocs.honolulu.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-20510/20170428-hart-recovery-plan.pdf |archive-date=August 31, 2017 |access-date=August 31, 2017 |publisher=Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation |page=19}}</ref>
*September 2014 – HART canceled the initial tender for the first nine stations after the bids were higher than budget. "The lowest bid by Nan, Inc. came in at $294.5 million, or $110 million more than the $184 million the transit authority had budgeted." The first trips on the railway are expected to be delayed, probably until 2018.<ref>{{Cite news |date=September 10, 2014 |title=HART cancels bids for first 9 rail stations |work=[[KITV]] |url=http://m.kitv.com/news/hart-cancels-bids-for-first-9-rail-stations/27967000 |url-status=dead |access-date=November 27, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129163425/http://m.kitv.com/news/hart-cancels-bids-for-first-9-rail-stations/27967000 |archive-date=November 29, 2014}}</ref>
*November 2015 – FTA withholds payment of a $250&nbsp;million allotment until the council could show it had sufficient funding to complete the project.<ref>{{Cite web |date=December 15, 2015 |title=Year in Review 2015: Honolulu's rail transit project |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/news/2015/12/15/year-in-review-2015-honolulus-rail-transit-project.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170905142603/https://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/news/2015/12/15/year-in-review-2015-honolulus-rail-transit-project.html |archive-date=September 5, 2017 |access-date=September 5, 2017 |website=Pacific Business Review}}</ref>
*January 2016 – Five year extension to the General Excise Tax surcharge adopted to add $1.2&nbsp;billion in funding.<ref name="HartRecoveryPlan2017" />
*May 2016 – HART chairwoman [[Colleen Hanabusa]] shared a confidential document detailing budget estimates as of March 1, 2016, showing that the rail project is expected to cost $6.9&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{Cite web |date=May 14, 2016 |title=Honolulu Rail Price Estimate Jumps To $6.9B |url=http://www.civilbeat.com/2016/05/honolulu-rail-price-estimate-jumps-to-6-9b/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160515111254/http://www.civilbeat.com/2016/05/honolulu-rail-price-estimate-jumps-to-6-9b/ |archive-date=May 15, 2016 |access-date=May 16, 2016 |website=[[Honolulu Civil Beat]]}}</ref>
*April 2016 – An audit of the project by the City criticized HART for using outdated financial figures and budgets, lack of documentation for "change orders", and warned the HART estimates of the cost overruns were unreliable.<ref>{{Cite web |date=April 15, 2016 |title=City audit calls HART's finances, plans 'outdated and unreliable' |url=http://khon2.com/2016/04/15/city-releases-audit-of-honolulu-authority-for-rapid-transportation/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170905051555/http://khon2.com/2016/04/15/city-releases-audit-of-honolulu-authority-for-rapid-transportation/ |archive-date=September 5, 2017 |access-date=September 4, 2017 |website=[[KHON-TV|KHON2]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=April 15, 2016 |title=Audit slams Honolulu rail agency over management, costs |work=Honolulu Star Advertiser |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2016/04/15/breaking-news/audit-slams-honolulu-rail-agency-over-management-costs/ |url-status=live |access-date=September 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170905050710/http://www.staradvertiser.com/2016/04/15/breaking-news/audit-slams-honolulu-rail-agency-over-management-costs/ |archive-date=September 5, 2017}}</ref> HART officials disputed the audit's findings.
*May 2016 – The FTA revealed that they estimate the total cost as $8.1 billion for the {{convert|20|mi|km|abbr=on}} line. In addition completion of the rail system would be delayed nearly five years until December 2024, versus HART's federal funding agreement stating that full line service from East Kapolei to Ala Moana Center would start in January 2020.<ref>{{Cite news |date=May 17, 2016 |title=Add 5 years and $1B for rail, federal agency says |language=en-US |work=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/hawaii-news/add-5-years-and-1b-for-rail-federal-agency-says/ |url-status=live |access-date=December 10, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611062648/http://www.staradvertiser.com/hawaii-news/add-5-years-and-1b-for-rail-federal-agency-says/ |archive-date=June 11, 2016}}</ref>
*June 2016 – Report from Jacobs Engineering, the project management oversight contractor, says that under a worst-case scenario the final cost would $10.79&nbsp;billion.<ref name="Jacobsworstcase" />
*August 2016 – Dan Grabauskas resigns as CEO and executive director of HART but will be the official CEO until October 2016. From August until October, the Department of Transportation Service Director Mike Formby served as interim CEO.<ref name="KHON2016-08-16" /><ref name="StarAdvertiser2016-08-16">{{Cite news |last=Honoré |first=Marcel |date=August 18, 2016 |title=Grabauskas resigns as HART's chief executive |work=[[Star-Advertiser]] |location=[[Honolulu]] |url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2016/08/18/breaking-news/grabauskas-resigns-as-harts-chief-executive/ |url-status=live |access-date=January 11, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023045350/http://www.staradvertiser.com/2016/08/18/breaking-news/grabauskas-resigns-as-harts-chief-executive/ |archive-date=October 23, 2018}}</ref><ref name="HNN2016-08-18">{{Cite news |last1=Daysog |first1=Rick |last2=Kawano |first2=Lynn |date=August 18, 2016 |title=Outgoing rail CEO ruffled feathers, struggled with cost overruns |work=[[Hawaii News Now]] |location=[[Honolulu]] |url=http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/32792174/hart-ceo-dan-grabauskas-resigns/ |url-status=live |access-date=January 11, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180112052241/http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/32792174/hart-ceo-dan-grabauskas-resigns |archive-date=January 12, 2018}}</ref>
*October 2016 – Krishniah N. Murthy named interim CEO and executive director of HART and served in this position until December 2017.<ref name="PacificBusinessNews2016-12-28">{{Cite news |last=Shimogawa |first=Duane |date=December 28, 2016 |title=Former HART CEO Dan Grabauskas starts own consulting firm |work=[[American City Business Journals|Pacific Business News]] |location=[[Honolulu]] |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/news/2016/12/28/former-hart-ceo-dan-grabauskas-starts-own.html |url-status=live |access-date=January 11, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200922041009/https://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/news/2016/12/28/former-hart-ceo-dan-grabauskas-starts-own.html |archive-date=September 22, 2020}}</ref>
*April 2017 – HART sent a "Recovery Plan" to the FTA which concluded that completion of the original 21 station route was the only viable plan. The new project cost given is $8.165&nbsp;billion with media reports indicating that after financing costs are included it will be over $10&nbsp;billion. Opening of part of the system, from East Kapolei to Aloha Stadium, is scheduled for the end of 2020 with final completion of the full route by December 2025. The project is reported to be 36 percent complete as of March 2017.<ref name="HARTcommitted" /><ref name="HARTrecoverplan" />
*July 2017 – Andrew Robbins named new CEO and executive director of HART at a base salary of $317,000, replacing interim CEO and Executive Director Krishniah N. Murthy in December 2017.<ref name="PacificBusinessNews2016-12-28" /><ref name="StarAdvertiser2017-07-31">{{Cite news |last=Honoré |first=Marcel |date=July 31, 2017 |title=HART board selects new executive director |work=[[Star-Advertiser]] |location=[[Honolulu]] |url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2017/07/31/breaking-news/hart-board-selects-new-executive-director/ |url-status=live |access-date=January 11, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731235209/http://www.staradvertiser.com/2017/07/31/breaking-news/hart-board-selects-new-executive-director/ |archive-date=July 31, 2017}}</ref>
*September 2017 – A new law is enacted to extend and increase taxes to raise an additional $2.4&nbsp;billion for the project. The GET surcharge is extended by three years to 2030 (generating about $1&nbsp;billion) and a surcharge of one percent is placed on the statewide hotel room tax for 13 years (generating $1.3&nbsp;billion).<ref name="Sep17taxespassed" /><ref name="Sep17Govsignsbill" /> HART submits a new recovery plan to the FTA with an estimated final cost of $9.02&nbsp;billion with savings attributed to reduced financing costs given the new taxes.<ref name="CostDropped1billion" />
*January 2020 – Andrew Robbins, executive director and CEO of the Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation, said the first 10 miles of the Honolulu rail system would be completed by December 2020 as predicted, and will also be ready to run passenger service between Kapolei and Aloha Stadium three months earlier, by October 20, 2020. Robbins said he was so confident of the new date that he was willing to stick his neck out.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Pennybacker |first=Mindy |date=January 9, 2020 |title=Honolulu's rail will be ready to run by Oct. 20, HART chief Andrew Robbins says |url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2020/01/09/hawaii-news/rail-will-start-running-oct-20-robbins-says/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201005053645/https://www.staradvertiser.com/2020/01/09/hawaii-news/rail-will-start-running-oct-20-robbins-says/ |archive-date=October 5, 2020 |access-date=September 11, 2020 |website=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |language=en-US}}</ref>
*May 2020 – "Completion of the first 10-mile segment of the line from East Kapolei to Aloha Stadium, originally scheduled for October, will be delayed by about eight weeks, according to Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation executive director Andrew Robbins... And the city, which had forecast opening the line to riders by December, has pushed that date back to next March."<ref>{{Cite web |date=May 16, 2020 |title=Editorial: COVID-19 brings more delays and money problems for Honolulu's rail |url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2020/05/16/editorial/our-view/editorial-covid-19-brings-more-delays-and-money-problems-for-honolulus-rail/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201004232616/https://www.staradvertiser.com/2020/05/16/editorial/our-view/editorial-covid-19-brings-more-delays-and-money-problems-for-honolulus-rail/ |archive-date=October 4, 2020 |access-date=September 20, 2020 |website=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |language=en-US}}</ref>
*June 2020 – "More recently, the FTA has been projecting the project would be finished in September 2026, and insisted that the city incorporate that later date into its 2019 rail 'recovery plan.'"<ref>{{Cite web |last=Dayton |first=Kevin |date=June 26, 2020 |title=Scheduled 2025 opening date for 20-mile rail line being pushed into 2026 |url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2020/06/26/hawaii-news/scheduled-2025-opening-date-for-20-mile-rail-line-being-pushed-into-2026/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200917033121/https://www.staradvertiser.com/2020/06/26/hawaii-news/scheduled-2025-opening-date-for-20-mile-rail-line-being-pushed-into-2026/ |archive-date=September 17, 2020 |access-date=September 10, 2020 |website=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |language=en-US}}</ref>
*July 2020 – The city finally received much-anticipated proposals from private industry to finish the project's major remaining construction work and then run the system for its first 30 years. The bids won't be publicly released until the contract is awarded by unidentified officials.<ref>{{Cite web |date=July 25, 2020 |title=Rail's P3 Proposals Finally Arrive But Costs Remain Sealed |url=https://www.civilbeat.org/2020/07/rails-p3-proposals-finally-arrive-but-costs-remain-sealed/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200916015529/https://www.civilbeat.org/2020/07/rails-p3-proposals-finally-arrive-but-costs-remain-sealed/ |archive-date=September 16, 2020 |access-date=September 10, 2020 |website=Honolulu Civil Beat |language=en}}</ref>
*September 2020 – One of the PPP bidders for the final city center segment from Middle Street to Ala Moana Center revealed themselves during a recent quarterly earnings call. Ronald Tutor, CEO of Tutor Perini, disclosed that his company is part of the Tutor Perini / Parsons joint venture for the final segment of Honolulu rail. While HART estimated that this last stretch would cost $1.4&nbsp;billion, Tutor stated that his company's bid was “over $2&nbsp;billion.”<ref>{{Cite web |date=September 18, 2020 |title=Honolulu Rail P3 Bidder Wants More Than $2 Billion For The Final Stretch |url=https://www.civilbeat.org/2020/09/honolulu-rail-p3-bidder-wants-more-than-2-billion-for-the-final-stretch/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200928150751/https://www.civilbeat.org/2020/09/honolulu-rail-p3-bidder-wants-more-than-2-billion-for-the-final-stretch/ |archive-date=September 28, 2020 |access-date=September 20, 2020 |website=Honolulu Civil Beat |language=en}}</ref>
*October 2020 – “The estimated cost of rail has jumped once again, bringing the construction and interest tab to the $10&nbsp;billion threshold. The mayor tells us it will probably grow more, and the shortfall to pay for it all now tops more than $1.2&nbsp;billion.”<ref>{{Cite web |date=October 16, 2020 |title=Rail swells to $10B to build and finance, gap now $1.2B as tax sinks |url=https://www.khon2.com/local-news/rail-swells-to-10b-to-build-and-finance-gap-now-1-2b-as-tax-sinks/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201025170419/https://www.khon2.com/local-news/rail-swells-to-10b-to-build-and-finance-gap-now-1-2b-as-tax-sinks/ |archive-date=October 25, 2020 |access-date=November 3, 2020 |website=[[KHON-TV|KHON2]] |language=en-US}}</ref>
*November 2020 – In an effort to keep $250&nbsp;million in federal funding from lapsing at the end of the year, Mayor Kirk Caldwell bypassed HART CEO Andrew Robbins and sent a letter to the Federal Transit Authority requesting a one-year extension through the end of 2021. A rough outline of a plan included in the letter suggested a total cost of $11.2&nbsp;billion including approximately $1&nbsp;billion in financing costs, and a completion date of 2033.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Pang |first=Gordon Y. K. |date=November 18, 2020 |title=Mayor Kirk Caldwell: Rail cost now $11B, won't be completed until 2033 |url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2020/11/18/hawaii-news/caldwell-rail-cost-now-11b-wont-be-completed-until-2033/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201127171118/https://www.staradvertiser.com/2020/11/18/hawaii-news/caldwell-rail-cost-now-11b-wont-be-completed-until-2033/ |archive-date=November 27, 2020 |access-date=November 28, 2020 |website=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |language=en-US}}</ref>
*December 2020 – HART received bids for the city center segment from two private-sector teams: $2.775&nbsp;billion by City Center Connection Group and $2.73&nbsp;billion by Imua Transit Honolulu, vs HART's budget of $1.4&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{Cite web |date=November 9, 2021 |title=How Rail Got to $12.45 Billion and 11 Years Late |url=https://www.hawaiibusiness.com/hart-history-hawaii-rail-project-when-finished-budget/ |access-date=April 28, 2023 |website=Hawaii Business Magazine |language=en-US}}</ref>
*March 2021 – Under new leadership, HART announces an updated, official completion date of 2031,<ref name="hart2031" /> with revenue service on the initial segment from Kapolei to Aloha Stadium beginning by the end of 2022.<ref name="KHON 2022-03-31">{{Cite news |last=Rodriguez |first=Max |date=March 31, 2022 |title=Honolulu rail project gets estimated time arrival |work=[[KHON-TV|KHON2]] |url=https://www.khon2.com/local-news/honolulu-rail-project-gets-estimated-time-arrival/ |url-status=live |access-date=April 20, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220421022815/https://www.khon2.com/local-news/honolulu-rail-project-gets-estimated-time-arrival/ |archive-date=April 21, 2022}}</ref>
*December 2021 – “The head of the Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation says next summer is the earliest the rail system could begin partial operations.” <ref>{{Cite web |date=December 10, 2021 |title=Summer 2022 is the earliest the rail could begin partial operations, HART CEO says |url=https://www.hawaiipublicradio.org/local-news/2021-12-10/summer-2022-is-the-earliest-the-rail-could-begin-partial-operations-hart-ceo-says |access-date=April 28, 2023 |website=Hawai'i Public Radio |language=en}}</ref>
*April 2022 – HART announces tight gage and weld modifications have been completed, with final 90-day testing to begin in the summer.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Ufi |first=Elizabeth |date=April 13, 2022 |title=Rail repairs made from Kapolei to Aloha Stadium |work=[[KHON-TV|KHON2]] |url=https://www.khon2.com/news/rail-repairs-made-from-kapolei-to-aloha-stadium/ |url-status=live |access-date=April 20, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220421022821/https://www.khon2.com/news/rail-repairs-made-from-kapolei-to-aloha-stadium/ |archive-date=April 21, 2022}}</ref>
*June 2022 – "The Honolulu Authority for Rapid Transportation says it’s hopeful residents will be using trains by the end of the year – even as construction in the urban corridor continues."<ref>{{Cite web |last=Solina |first=Samie |date=June 9, 2022 |title=People could be riding the Honolulu rail by the end of 2022, HART's CEO says |url=https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/2022/06/09/hart-residents-could-be-riding-honolulu-rail-by-end-2022/ |access-date=April 28, 2023 |website=Hawaii News Now |language=en}}</ref>
*August 2022 – HART begins the 90-day trial testing phase.<ref>{{Cite news |date=August 31, 2022 |title=HART begins trial running on Honolulu rail line |work=Mass Transit |location=Honolulu, Hawaii |url=https://www.masstransitmag.com/rail/infrastructure/press-release/21279326/honolulu-authority-for-rapid-transportation-hart-hart-begins-trial-running-on-honolulu-rail-line |access-date=September 23, 2022}}</ref>
*September 2022 – "The Federal Transit Administration has approved the Honolulu rail's financial recovery plan which outlines a truncated version of the rail line, 1.25 miles short of Ala Moana Center."<ref name="HPR202209">{{Cite web |date=September 30, 2022 |title=Shortened Honolulu rail plan approved by Federal Transit Administration |url=https://www.hawaiipublicradio.org/local-news/2022-09-30/shortened-honolulu-rail-plan-approved-by-federal-transit-administration |access-date=April 28, 2023 |website=Hawai'i Public Radio |language=en}}</ref>
*May 2023 – Honolulu Mayor [[Rick Blangiardi]] and the Department of Transportation Services announce that Segment&nbsp;1 (the first nine stations from East Kapolei to Aloha Stadium) will open to the public at 2&nbsp;p.m. on June 30, 2023. Segment&nbsp;2 (four stations between Aloha Stadium and Middle Street–Kalihi Transit Center, serving the [[Daniel K. Inouye International Airport]]) is announced to open in the summer of 2025, and that Segment&nbsp;3 (six stations from Middle Street–Kalihi Transit Center to Civic Center) will open in 2031.<ref>{{Cite web |date=May 10, 2023 |title='Let's get ready to ride': city officials prepare to roll out Honolulu rail on June 30 |url=https://www.hawaiipublicradio.org/local-news/2023-05-10/lets-get-ready-to-ride-city-officials-announce-honolulu-rails-opening-date |access-date=May 14, 2023 |website=Hawai'i Public Radio |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Wanek-Libman |first=Mischa |date=May 22, 2023 |title=Honolulu's rail line will open June 30: The first nine stations will connect East Kapolei to Aloha Stadium with two planned extensions in 2025 and 2031. |work=Mass Transit Magazine |url=https://www.masstransitmag.com/rail/article/53061139/honolulus-rail-line-will-open-june-30 |access-date=May 22, 2023 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20230522182352/https://www.masstransitmag.com/rail/article/53061139/honolulus-rail-line-will-open-june-30 |archive-date=May 22, 2023}}</ref>
*June 2023 – Skyline Segment&nbsp;1 begins operations. The "Skyline" name is announced two weeks before opening,<ref name="KITV 2023-06-16">{{Cite news |last=Kabir |first=Shanila |date=June 16, 2023 |title=Oahu's upcoming rail system is officially named 'Skyline' |work=KITV |url=https://www.kitv.com/news/business/oahus-upcoming-rail-system-is-officially-named-skyline/article_80410be2-0cb3-11ee-939b-7fad8a424fbb.html |access-date=June 17, 2023}}</ref><ref name="SA 2023-06-16">{{Cite news |last=Bauer |first=Ian |date=June 16, 2023 |title=City officials give Honolulu rail system an official name |work=[[Honolulu Star-Advertiser]] |url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2023/06/16/breaking-news/city-officials-give-honolulu-rail-system-an-official-name/ |access-date=June 17, 2023}}</ref> inspired by the Hawaiian [[White tern|manu-o-Kū]].<ref>{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EIsqEX7Im1w |title=How the Manu o Kū influenced Skyline |date=2024-05-01 |last=Honolulu Department of Transportation Services |access-date=2024-06-15 |via=YouTube}}</ref> This establishes an official name, having been colloquially termed "rail" for much of its development.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Cheung |first=Candace |date=2023-07-01 |title='It's about time': Honolulu's long-awaited rail system has grand opening |url=https://www.courthousenews.com/its-about-time-honolulus-long-awaited-rail-system-has-grand-opening |access-date=2025-12-26 |website=Courthouse News Service |language=en-us}}</ref>
*June 2024 – Electrification of Segment&nbsp;2 begins. The service operation date is revised from summer 2025 to late 2025.<ref name="energized" /><ref name="HARTConstruction" />
*March 2025 – Mayor Blangiardi announces that Segment&nbsp;2 is scheduled to open on October&nbsp;1, 2025, with construction of Segment&nbsp;3 beginning the same year.<ref name="segment2announce" />
*August 2025 – Segment&nbsp;2's first day of passenger service is announced as October&nbsp;16, 2025.<ref name="segment2oct16a">{{Cite web |title=Skyline - Schedule |url=https://www.honolulu.gov/dts/skyline-schedule/ |access-date=August 26, 2025 |website=Honolulu Department of Transportation Services |language=en}}</ref><ref name="segment2oct16b" /><ref name=segment2oct16c /><ref name=segment2oct16d /> Construction begins on Segment&nbsp;3 and is expected to be completed in 2030.<ref>{{Cite Instagram |postid=DNOrT5qy0k1 |user=hnl.transit |title=This morning, @honolulu_rail_transit (HART) held a blessing and groundbreaking ceremony at the future site of the Ka'ākaukukui (Civic Center) Station in Kaka'ako to mark the start of construction on Segment 3 of Skyline! |date=August 11, 2025 |access-date=August 18, 2025}}</ref>
*October 2025 – Segment&nbsp;2 is officially opened to the public.<ref name=segment2open />

== In popular culture ==
* In the 2014 American film ''[[Godzilla (2014 film)|Godzilla]]'', the [[MUTO]] monster attacks and destroys a train and a viaduct of the Skyline, which was actually under construction at the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2014/05/16/features/good-monster-film-ruined-by-humans/amp/|title=Good monster film ruined by humans|publisher=Honolulu Star-Advertiser|date=2014-05-16|access-date=2024-05-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xMdhMnD05sY|title=Godzilla (2014) – Monorail Fight Scene (3/10)|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=2020-03-02|access-date=2022-11-22}}{{cbignore}}</ref>

